<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mets' Piazza on 15-Day DL </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MONTREAL (AP) -- Mike Piazza wasn't happy.  
</P>
<P>
	``I did not want to go on the disabled list,'' the All-Star  
catcher said today after the New York Mets put him on the 15-day 
disabled list because of a sprained right knee. ``I felt like I 
could play in a week.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Piazza, injured during a rundown Friday night, was sent to New  
York the following day, and an MRI revealed a sprained ligament. 
</P>
<P>
	Mets team physician Dr. David Altcheck examined Piazza on Sunday  
and confirmed the medial collateral ligament in Piazza's right knee 
had been sprained, though he found no damage to the posterior 
cruciate ligament, as first had been thought. 
</P>
<P>
	``The doctor made it clear that if I do play, and I run the  
bases and suddenly have to change directions it could be a full 
tear and that would mean surgery,'' Piazza said from New York 
during a telephone conference call. ``Considering that possibility, 
I figure that this is for the best.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Mets have won both games that Piazza has missed and will  
have to make due without him for 2-3 weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	Mets outfielder Bobby Bonilla acknowledged that Piazza's absence  
from the New York lineup will be hard on the team's fans. 
</P>
<P>
	``They might be a little disappointed with Mike not being there  
tomorrow,'' Bonilla said, looking ahead to Monday's home opener. 
``You know, you'll have a lot of kids wanting to see him play, but 
it's a pretty good baseball team. We shouldn't really miss a beat, 
which will be nice for Mike. He can feel comfortable to make sure 
he gets back on time and make sure he does it right. 
</P>
<P>
	Piazza, acquired last year from the Florida Marlins after he  
left the Los Angeles Dodgers, is starting a $91 million, seven-year 
contract. He is hitting .429 (9-for-21) with two homers and a 
team-leading eight RBIs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
