<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 6 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	More US Jets Headed for Yugoslavia  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Pentagon has announced that 82 U.S. planes  
will join NATO forces now conducting airstrikes over Yugoslavia. 
Allies were expected to add dozens more aircraft within days. ``The 
addition of these aircraft will allow us to ... expand the number 
of strikes over any 24-hour-day period,'' Pentagon spokesman 
Kenneth Bacon said. But it could take a month for 24 Apache attack 
helicopters to be ready for use from a base in Albania. Their 
introduction would mark an escalation of the war and for the first 
time allow close-to-the-ground, direct strikes against Serb troops 
and tanks during persistent bad weather. 

</P>
<P>
	Mother of Captured GI Breaks Down  
</P>
<P>
	MONTEBELLO, Calif. (AP) -- The mother of one of the American  
soldiers captured on the Yugoslav border broke down at a ceremony 
attended by hundreds yesterday. ``He went on a mission of peace. 
This was not supposed to happen,'' Vivian Ramirez said of her son, 
Army Staff Sgt. Andrew Ramirez. Ramirez, 24, Staff Sgt. Christopher 
Stone, 25, of Smiths Creek, Mich., and Spc. Steven M. Gonzales, 22, 
of Huntsville, Texas, were captured March 31 while patrolling the 
Yugoslav-Macedonia border. Shouts of encouragement for Mrs. Ramirez 
came from the audience of about 300 people gathered before the 
veterans memorial at Montebello Park. 

</P>
<P>
	FAA Tests Computers for Y2K Trouble  
</P>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- The Federal Aviation Administration has passed a  
live test of its new fixes to correct the year 2000 computer bug. 
The test involved the forwarding of computer clocks at Denver 
International Airport to the hour of midnight Dec. 31, 1999. An air 
traffic controller and the pilot of an approaching F-A-A plane then 
held a conversation that safely bridged the gap of the new century. 
Officials say the computers were able to read the new year 
successfully. The year 2000 glitch stems from computers not being 
able to read the date properly, a problem some officials believe 
could disrupt air traffic. 

</P>
<P>
	India Tests Nuclear-Capable Missile  
</P>
<P>
	NEW DELHI, India (AP) -- Defying appeals from the United States  
to put its nuclear program on hold, India has tested an upgraded 
version of its intermediate-range missile. Information Minister 
Pramod Mahajan told a hastily summoned news conference that the 
Agni II ballistic missile was successfully launched at 10 a.m. 
local time (12:30 a.m. EDT). Indian news agencies quoted government 
officials as saying Pakistan was given advanced warning. The test 
comes after India conducted a series of underground nuclear 
explosions last year that prompted Pakistan to respond with tests 
of its own, raising international fears of a nuclear arms race 
between the two belligerent nations. 

</P>
<P>
	Gore Says Draft Won't Be Reinstated  
</P>
<P>
	WAUSAU, Wis. (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore told a Boy Scout  
yesterday there were no plans to reinstate the draft, despite the 
NATO bombing campaign in Yugoslavia. The draft question by 
14-year-old Joe Wiesneski, was the most pointed about the conflict 
in Kosovo posed to Gore at a campaign fund-raiser. ``There is very 
little support for moving away from the volunteer Army,'' Gore 
said. President Clinton has repeatedly said he had no plan to send 
ground troops to fight in Kosovo. 

</P>
<P>
	Welfare Rolls Fall Again  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President yesterday used the latest report of  
shrinking welfare rolls -- cut nearly in half since 1993 -- to prod 
Congress for child care, housing and transportation programs that 
he said will move even more welfare recipients into jobs. He also 
announced final regulations that give states greater leeway in 
using federal welfare grants to set up such programs themselves. 
Nationally, just over 7.6 million Americans were receiving public 
assistance at the end of December, down from almost 8 million at 
the end of September and 14.3 million in 1994. 

</P>
<P>
	Home of Suspected Chinese Spy Raided  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal agents searched the New Mexico home of  
a suspected spy who was fired from his job at a Los Alamos nuclear 
laboratory last month. The raid yesterday at the single-story brick 
and wooden home of Wen Ho Lee pierced the tranquillity of the 
suburban neighborhood where the Taiwan-born American scientist 
lives. ``There was a lot of commotion going on. People were driving 
by, neighbors were outside and agents were coming and going,'' said 
a neighbor who also works at the Los Alamos laboratory. 

</P>
<P>
	Two Groups To Submit Bids for A's  
</P>
<P>
	OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) -- Two investment groups will make bids to  
buy the Oakland Athletics this week, a team representative said. 
The groups will submit separate bids on a one-time offer to buy the 
franchise for $120 million, according to a representative of the 
Oakland-Alameda County Coliseum Authority in the potential sale. 
Local government officials are worried that the A's may move, 
possibly to San Jose. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAN BOYLAN  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
