<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Failure of WTO Talks Deprives China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SHANGHAI, China (AP) -- By failing to agree with Washington on  
joining the World Trade Organization, China avoided the pain of 
exposing its industries to foreign competition but missed a chance 
to expand exports and modernize. 
</P>
<P>
	State banks and companies remain shielded behind walls of  
tariffs and import bans, along with farms that employ hundreds of 
millions of Chinese but are inefficient and not competitive. 
</P>
<P>
	The failure of talks in Washington deprived visiting Premier Zhu  
Rongji of a potent weapon to push forward his sweeping free-market 
reforms that have cost millions of jobs in an attempt to turn 
around money-losing state industry. 
</P>
<P>
	``Joining the WTO would have forced China to reform at a faster  
pace. Zhu Rongji still can do it, but China will move at its own 
pace and reform bit by bit,'' said Li Kui Wai, an economist at the 
City University of Hong Kong. 
</P>
<P>
	Other losers included Chinese telecommunications and high-tech  
companies that would have gotten better access to investment and 
foreign technology. 
</P>
<P>
	Membership in the WTO, which regulates world trade, would give  
China a say in global trade rules and protect it from unilateral 
trade sanctions. For textiles, steel and some other goods, that 
would mean an end to U.S. import quotas. 
</P>
<P>
	Although China agreed to drop bans on U.S. wheat and citrus even  
without membership, farmers were spared for now from competing with 
other, cheaper agricultural imports. A reform advocate said that 
while the latest concessions will hurt some farmers, China will 
benefit from the pressure. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the price China must pay. In the long term, this will  
help to promote agricultural modernization,'' said Chi Fulin, 
director of a government think tank, the China Institute for Reform 
and Development. 
</P>
<P>
	Most countries already give China the low tariffs and other  
trade privileges it would get in the WTO. But Chi said membership 
still could help Beijing secure those stable trade terms and force 
Chinese companies to improve. 
</P>
<P>
	``Joining the WTO will do more good than bad, although China  
will face more competition and risks,'' he said by telephone from 
his office in the southern city of Haikou. 
</P>
<P>
	After 13 years of on-again, off-again talks, China appeared  
increasingly intent in recent months on membership and showed new 
willingness to offer concessions. Beijing licensed more foreign 
banks and insurance companies and agreed that even without WTO 
membership, it would allow more foreign airline flights. 
</P>
<P>
	But some officials and academics argued China was giving up too  
much. They feared that too big a foreign presence could destroy 
companies, leading to layoffs and social upheaval that might 
threaten communist power. 
</P>
<P>
	Radical market-opening moves could widen growing gaps in wealth  
and income. Cheaper imports would deliver lower prices for 
consumers but undercut farm towns and areas dominated by state 
industry. 
</P>
<P>
	Danger spots include state banks, which have only just begun  
reforms meant to free them of an avalanche of bad loans to failing 
state firms and make them profitable. 
</P>
<P>
	Regulators have resisted giving foreigners more than a tiny  
slice of the financial industry, for fear diverting savings from 
state banks could cause a financial collapse. 
</P>
<P>
	``China is really reluctant to open its financial markets,  
because they don't want to lose control,'' said Li. 
</P>
<P>
	Other weaknesses are service industries ranging from travel  
agencies to insurance, where Chinese companies lag in technology 
and skills. 
</P>
<P>
	China had said it would need grace periods of up to 20 years to  
phase out protections for agricultural and service industries. 
</P>
<P>
	China already has tried to inject competition into the market on  
its own. While Zhu was in Washington, Beijing announced it was 
breaking up state-owned China Telecom, the phone monopoly, into 
four companies to spur innovation. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet without the reassuring framework of WTO rules, it will get  
harder to attract investors already skittish because of the Asian 
financial crisis, said Li, the Hong Kong researcher. 
</P>
<P>
	That could wind up knocking up to 1 percent off economic growth  
over the next two to three years, he predicted. 
</P>
<P>
	``Foreign investment is not free these days. So in a sense,  
China suffers for that,'' he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
