<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kosovo Clouds Holocaust Memorial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Two thousand people gathered at a Manhattan  
synagogue Sunday to commemorate victims of the Holocaust while 
remembering that ethnic persecution continues in Europe today. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ethnic cleansing, genocide, is happening as I speak,'' said  
Benjamin Meed, president of the American Gathering of Jewish 
Holocaust Survivors. ``It can happen to anyone, to any group of 
people. The slaughter of Kosovo and in other places must be brought 
to an end.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In Los Angeles, Holocaust survivors, Jewish leaders and  
politicians gathered with several hundred others on Sunday at the 
Simon Wiesenthal Center and Museum of Tolerance to observe Yom 
Hashoah, or Holocaust Day. 
</P>
<P>
	The Los Angeles gathering also served to open an exhibit  
chronicling the life and work of 90-year-old Wiesenthal, the famed 
Nazi hunter who spent 53 years seeking nearly 1,100 German war 
criminals around the world. 
</P>
<P>
	Wiesenthal resides in Austria and did not attend the event.  
</P>
<P>
	The New York ceremony opened with four dozen Holocaust survivors  
-- all of them women dressed in black, and many of them elderly -- 
lighting candles in memory of those who perished. 
</P>
<P>
	It was dedicated to the SS St. Louis, a ship that set sail from  
Europe 60 years ago and was denied entry by both Cuba and the 
United States. Most of the 937 refugees on board were Jews; they 
were sent back to Europe and only 240 survived the war. 
</P>
<P>
	``Think for the moment what was going through the minds of the  
Jews as they stood on the boat able to see the lights of Miami,'' 
said New York Gov. George Pataki, adding: ``Our government should 
have known they would likely be condemned to death.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In Los Angeles, Holocaust survivor Morris Shulman was among  
those attending. 
</P>
<P>
	Born in Germany in 1917, the 82-year-old Jewish cabinetmaker  
considers his liberation from the Buchenwald concentration camp a 
rebirth. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was freed 54 years ago exactly. April 11, 1945, at about 1  
o'clock. I weighed 72 pounds,'' said Shulman, whose parents, three 
sisters and two brothers were killed in concentration camps. 
</P>
<P>
	Pausing to smile, he added, ``It's a joyful day. My second  
birthday.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
