<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bid City, IOC Share PR Firm </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	The public relations firm helping the International Olympic  
Committee repair its scandal-battered image has been hired by 
organizers of Toronto's effort to win the 2008 Summer Games, 
according to a published report. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision by Toronto's bid committee means that Hill &AMP;  
Knowlton Inc. will represent both the IOC and a city that must 
lobby the IOC for the right to hold the games. 
</P>
<P>
	In its April 12 edition, PRWeek magazine reported that Hill &AMP;  
Knowlton has been chosen over Edelman, GPC Canada and Grey 
Advertising subsidiaries GCI Group and APCO Associates, who pitched 
jointly for the business. 
</P>
<P>
	Jeff Evensen, coordinator of Toronto's bid, told the magazine  
that the bid committee had no reservations about any possible 
conflict of interest. 
</P>
<P>
	Hill &AMP; Knowlton also has stressed that representing competing  
for the Toronto account while representing the IOC did not pose a 
conflict of interest. 
</P>
<P>
	Telephone calls by The Associated Press to two representatives  
of Hill &AMP; Knowlton were not returned Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	The IOC is struggling to clean up its image in the aftermath of  
the bribery scandal involving Salt Lake City's bid for the 2002 
Winter Games, and any apparent conflict of interest could hurt that 
effort. 
</P>
<P>
	PRWeek quoted Len Brooks, a business ethics professor at  
Toronto's Rotman School of Management, as saying that Hill &AMP; 
Knowlton should erect a ``firewall'' between its IOC and Toronto 
teams, including separate filing and computer systems, to prevent 
the sharing of information that could give the bid committee an 
unfair advantage. 
</P>
<P>
	Hill &AMP; Knowlton's involvement with the Toronto bid committee  
while simultaneously representing the IOC was first reported in 
February by The Wall Street Journal. At the time, Hill &AMP; Knowlton 
spokesman Ron Hartwig said no company employee involved in the IOC 
job can work on the Toronto effort. 
</P>
<P>
	Besides Toronto, other cities seeking the 2008 Summer Games  
include Beijing; Paris; Osaka, Japan; and Seville, Spain. Others 
considering making a bid include Cairo; Istanbul; Kuala Lumpur, 
Malaysia; and Buenos Aires. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
