<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> MedPartners, California Reach Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- State negotiators have reached an agreement  
in principal that would hold MedPartners Inc. responsible for debts 
and claims against its California subsidiary and permit more than 
100 clinics seized by state regulators to remain open. 
</P>
<P>
	The agreement, which must be approved in U.S. Bankruptcy Court  
and state Superior Court, would end the state's monthlong battle 
with Alabama-based MedPartners over concerns that the financially 
troubled company would leave the state without paying its bills, 
and leave more than 1 million enrollees shopping for new doctors. 
</P>
<P>
	Details on how the agreement will be carried out still must be  
negotiated, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	General terms of the agreement were announced from Sacramento  
Friday after attorneys for both sides battled in a Los Angeles 
courtroom over the legality of the regulators' March 11 seizure of 
MedPartners Provider Network, the California subsidiary that 
manages business affairs for 117 clinics and more than 1,000 
doctors. 
</P>
<P>
	The agreement also calls for the clinics to be sold to  
``financially viable'' third parties. State officials said they 
would urge MedPartners to sell the clinics to California-based 
companies. 
</P>
<P>
	MedPartners Inc., squeezed by a falling share price and doctor  
discontent, said in November that it was quitting the physician 
management business. The company planned this year to sell or spin 
off 238 physician clinics and more than 13,000 affiliated doctors 
in 42 states. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
