<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) -- A top Honduran prison official, his  
wife and two bodyguards were killed when their car was ambushed by 
at least six gunmen, officials said Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Police said they suspect that organized crime was behind the  
killing Saturday of Col. Luis Alfonso Reyes Barahona, deputy 
director of the Honduran prison system. Reyes Barahona, a lawyer, 
had previously headed the police department in Tegucigalpa, the 
capital. 
</P>
<P>
	Reyes Barahona and his wife, Johanna, were spending the weekend  
in his native city of Yoro, 100 miles north of Tegucigalpa, said 
prison director Dimas Carbajal. They were driving near the city 
when the gunmen opened fire. 
</P>
<P>
	``The criminals fired like cowards and then burned the car, with  
all of its occupants,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- An elderly driver lost control of  
his car and ran over 22 people at an open-air fruit and vegetable 
market Sunday in Rio de Janeiro, police said. 
</P>
<P>
	Witnesses said the car was traveling at a high speed from the  
moment it left a garage, knocking over pedestrians and market 
stalls until it crashed into a building 250 yards down the street. 
</P>
<P>
	The car's driver, 85-year-old Evio Santos de Bustante, was  
apparently feeling ill when he lost control of the car, police 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The driver, a passenger and the 22 victims were all  
hospitalized. One of the injured was listed in serious condition. 
</P>
