<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NATO Attacks Said To Hit Civilians  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO's bombing of Serb targets in  
Kosovo continued today, despite the Orthodox Easter holiday. 
Yugoslavia reported six civilian deaths and 23 injuries in this 
morning's strikes. Tanjug, the official news agency, said the dead 
include a father and his 1-year-old daughter. According to Yugoslav 
officials, 300 civilians have been killed and 3,000 injured during 
the bombing campaign. There was no way to independently verify the 
figures. Yugoslavia does not disclose military casualties. 

</P>
<P>
	Americans Volunteer To Join KLA  
</P>
<P>
	YONKERS, N.Y. (AP) -- Wearing store-bought uniforms, hundreds of  
Americans showed up at a suburban New York hotel, volunteering to 
join the Kosovo Liberation Army. They want to take up arms against 
the Serbs as part of an effort to save hundreds of thousands of 
ethnic Albanians who have fled their decimated towns and villages. 
Most in the Yonkers parking lot had relatives there who are either 
dead or missing. 

</P>
<P>
	India Tests Nuclear-Capable Missile  
</P>
<P>
	NEW DELHI, India (AP) -- India today tested a missile capable of  
carrying a nuclear warhead, defying U.S. appeals for restraint in 
weapons testing and raising fears of a new arms race with 
neighboring Pakistan. White House spokesman Mike Hammer said the 
missile test ``appears to be out of step with positive developments 
in the political sphere.'' He said India's government informed the 
United States on Friday of its decision to test the missile. 

</P>
<P>
	Some Work Deaths Preventable  
</P>
<P>
	GENEVA (AP) -- Of the estimated 1.1 million work-related deaths  
occur each year, many could be prevented by better safety measures. 
That's according to the International Labor Organization, which 
said nearly 300,000 of these deaths stem from exposure to hazardous 
substances which caused cancer, heart and respiratory disease, the 
U.N. labor organization said. The ILO said an estimated 600,000 
lives each year could be saved if safety and information practices 
were improved. 

</P>
<P>
	Medicines May Prevent Colon Cancer  
</P>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- A combination of aspirin and  
cholesterol-lowering drugs used to prevent heart disease may also 
significantly lower the risk of colon cancer. New research suggests 
the common medicines appear to offer a potent -- if unintended -- 
shield against the cancer. The work is based on a new analysis of 
cholesterol-lowering drugs known as statins, already used by 
millions of Americans to keep their hearts healthy. 

</P>
<P>
	Television Bursting With Ads  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The number of ads cluttering up prime-time  
television is soaring, a study released today showed. An average 
hour of prime-time TV contained 15 minutes, 44 seconds of 
advertising last November, a jump of 25 seconds over the year 
before. Daytime network television is even more bloated by ads. The 
networks added 11 seconds of commercial time last year to crack the 
20-minute barrier: one-third of each hour in daytime is taken up by 
commercials. 

</P>
<P>
	Stocks Lower in Early Tokyo Trading  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The Nikkei Stock Average fell 163.55 points to  
16,692.08 in early trading on Monday. On Friday, the index gained 
8.94 points. 

</P>
