<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Nets Retire Williams' No. 52 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. (AP) -- Buck Williams, a blue-collar power  
forward who set 10 team records in eight seasons in New Jersey, had 
his No. 52 retired by the Nets today. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a special honor,'' Williams said before his number was  
raised to the rafters at the Continental Airlines Arena. ``I think 
every athlete thinks in terms of having their number retired.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The ceremony took place at halftime of the Nets' game against  
the New York Knicks. A first-round draft choice of the Nets in 
1981, Williams started his career in New Jersey and ended it this 
year after two seasons with New York. In between were seven seasons 
with the Portland Trail Blazers, with whom he twice went to the NBA 
Finals. 
</P>
<P>
	While Williams had fond memories of his time in New Jersey, many  
of his thoughts Sunday focused on the Knicks' struggles and the 
plight of coach Jeff Van Gundy, whose job reportedly is in 
jeopardy. 
</P>
<P>
	``Jeff is a phenomenal coach,'' Williams said. ``The Knicks  
would be doing themselves an injustice to fire coach Van Gundy. I 
think he has worked harder than a lot of the players.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Few people outworked Williams during his 17-year NBA career. He  
is the Nets' all-time leader in scoring (10,440), rebounds (7,576), 
games (635), minutes (23,100), field goals made (3,981), field 
goals attempted (7,234), free throws made (2,476), free throws 
attempted (3,818), offensive rebounds (2,588) and defensive 
rebounds (4,988). 
</P>
<P>
	``I think he got the most out of his talent and that's what you  
want to be able to say to every athlete,'' said Hall of Famer 
Willis Reed, a Nets senior vice president who coached Williams in 
New Jersey. 
</P>
<P>
	Williams' fondest memory with the Nets came in the spring of  
1984 when New Jersey eliminated defending champion Philadelphia in 
the first round of the playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	Former Nets center Mike Gminski said no one story or event can  
sum up Williams' career. He was just a player who showed up every 
night and gave everything he had. 
</P>
<P>
	``The amazing thing, and most people don't realize this, is that  
he was a power forward and he never weighed more than 225 pounds,'' 
Gminski said. ``He was so strong inside.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Five other Nets players have had their numbers retired -- Drazen  
Petrovic (3), Wendell Ladner (4), John Williamson (23), Bill 
Melchionni (25) and Julius Erving (32). 
</P>
</TEXT>
