<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-11 14:58:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Final Opening Day for Tiger Stadium </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- There once was an old hay market at the corner of  
Michigan and Trumbull. 
</P>
<P>
	That old hay market gave way to Bennett Park, which opened in  
1896. That gave way to Navin Field, which opened in 1912 and later 
became Briggs Stadium and Tiger Stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	When the Tigers play the Minnesota Twins tomorrow, it will mark  
the last home opener in Tiger Stadium. The team will move a few 
blocks away to Comerica Park to start the 2000 season. 
</P>
<P>
	``Oh, it's going to be awful hard on me, because I've spent  
every year of my adult life ... at Briggs Stadium and Tiger 
Stadium,'' Hall of Famer Al Kaline said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ernie Harwell, the beloved announcer who has been broadcasting  
from the corner since 1960, has been in the radio booth for two 
World Series championships at the ballpark. 
</P>
<P>
	Sparky Anderson came along in 1979 and managed the Tigers for  
the next 16 seasons. Under him, the Tigers won two division titles 
and a World Series championship. 
</P>
<P>
	The current manager, Larry Parrish, remembers the night when  
Sparky -- who never once played the outfield -- robbed him of a home 
run. It happened while Parrish, then playing for Texas, was facing 
Jack Morris. 
</P>
<P>
	``Jack threw me a fastball away and I hit it pretty good to  
right field,'' Parrish said. ``It went out of the ballpark. I ran 
around the bases.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Then Sparky stepped out of the dugout, arguing the ball went  
foul before leaving the stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	``He actually got the home plate umpire to overrule the first  
base umpire, and call it a foul ball,'' Parrish said. ``I had to go 
back up there and hit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After the game, a fan made his way to the clubhouse and wanted  
Parrish to autograph the ball. 
</P>
<P>
	``He said that he'd caught it, and he was sitting two rows  
inside the foul pole, in fair territory,'' Parrish said. ``So, 
Sparky got a home run taken away from me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Perhaps the most famous game came in the 1934 World Series, when  
St. Louis outfielder Ducky Medwick had to be pulled by baseball 
commissioner Kenesaw Mountain Landis. Fans threw garbage at Medwick 
after he crashed into Detroit third baseman Marv Owen. 
</P>
<P>
	The Tigers have played in the World Series nine times, winning  
four. Detroit also has held three All-Star games, including the one 
in 1971 in which Reggie Jackson homered into the light tower on the 
right-field roof. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is so much history in that place,'' Anderson said. ``It  
went all the way back to basically when Cobb played ... Gehrig and 
Ruth, all of them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bennett Park, the stadium's forerunner, was mainly a covered  
grandstand. Hundreds of fans crammed bleachers erected across the 
street. They were only slightly deterred by cloth drapes blocking 
their sight behind the outfield wall. 
</P>
<P>
	By 1911, team owner Frank Navin razed the old stands and built a  
new facility. Navin Field opened to a 6-5 Detroit victory before a 
crowd of 24,384 on April 20, 1912. 
</P>
<P>
	Also opening that day was Fenway Park in Boston, which next year  
will be alone as the oldest stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	The opening of Navin Field -- widely regarded as the beginning of  
Tiger Stadium -- should have been a front-page story. But the 
sinking of the Titanic five days earlier was still hot news. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1923, the original stands were double-decked. Walter Briggs  
took over the club after Navin died and added a second level to the 
bleachers and the right-field pavilion in 1936. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1938, Cherry Street, the northern boundary, was closed,  
enabling another expansion that essentially enclosed the park. It 
was renamed Briggs Stadium, held 53,000 and looked pretty much as 
it does today. 
</P>
<P>
	``What I'll miss least is the bullpen,'' reliever Todd Jones  
said. ``To me, it's a cross between a submarine and a prison.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Still, as a lover of baseball lore, Jones will be as sorry as  
anyone to see the club move. 
</P>
<P>
	``I love the place,'' he said. ``But more than that, I love how  
much it means to people.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
