<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sosa Finally Hits Homer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Seems like old times -- Sammy Sosa and Mark  
McGwire homering on the same day. 
</P>
<P>
	Sosa ended a 1-for-20 slump with a 441-foot homer to center  
field in the ninth inning of the Chicago Cubs' 9-6 loss to the 
Pittsburgh Pirates on Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	The homer -- Sosa's first since he hit No. 66 on Sept. 25 in  
Houston -- came in the Cubs' sixth game of the season. Before 
homering, Sosa was 0-for-10 with five strikeouts during the 
Pirates' three-game weekend sweep. 
</P>
<P>
	McGwire, who hit five homers in the final three days last season  
to edge Sosa 70-66 and set the record, hit his second of the season 
on Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Oh yeah? That's good,'' Sosa said. ``For me, I don't worry  
about it anymore. Last year is over, we are in 1999 now. I cannot 
come down here every day thinking about 1998, it's over.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sosa hit a Mike Williams fastball on a 0-1 pitch into the  
netting in Three Rivers Stadium's lower center-field seats. In his 
first four plate appearances Sunday, Sosa was 0-for-3 with two 
strikeouts and a walk. 
</P>
<P>
	Slow starts are nothing new for Sosa, who hit only one homer in  
the Cubs' first 10 games last season. He hit 65 in their final 153 
games. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're pitching me more carefully this year than ever,'' Sosa  
said. ``It feels great to get the first one. I was looking for 
anything up there. The home run came and I appreciate it, but I was 
looking for a base hit, anything.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sosa is hitting only .095, but manager Jim Riggleman expects the  
National League MVP to get untracked soon. 
</P>
<P>
	Sosa, who led the majors with 12 homers during spring training,  
and put on a show during batting practice Sunday, at one point 
hitting five straight long home runs. 
</P>
<P>
	``He hit a couple of (long fly balls) to right field yesterday,  
and that usually means good things are going to happen,'' Riggleman 
said. ``Sammy Sosa's going to have another great year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sosa drew a nice ovation after homering, in part because the  
solo shot didn't threaten the hometown Pirates' victory. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's great the fans haven't forgotten me yet,'' he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
