<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kentucky Derby Preps Roundup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Not long after trainer Nick Zito watched Wondertross finish  
sixth in Blue Grass Stakes at Keeneland, he was shouting, ``Go, 
Adonis, go.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With Zito listening to the live call, Adonis won the Wood  
Memorial on Saturday at Aqueduct. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're happy with Adonis and disappointed with Wondertross,''  
Zito said. 
</P>
<P>
	He will go after his third Kentucky victory -- following Strike  
the Gold (1991) and Go for Gin (1994) -- with at least Adonis and 
Stephen Go Even, winner of the Gallery Furniture.com Stakes on 
March 27 at Turfway Park. 
</P>
<P>
	Zito said Wondertross developed a breathing problem in finishing  
sixth in the Blue Grass won by Menifee and his Derby status was yet 
to be determined 
</P>
<P>
	While Menifee and at least the next four finishers in the  
eight-horse Toyota Blue Grass -- Cat Thief, Vicar, Kimberlite Pipe 
and Lemon Drop Kid -- are headed for the Derby on May 1, so is 
Valhol, who had not won a race until the Arkansas Derby on Saturday 
at Oaklawn Park. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Kentucky Derby is the crown jewel of all of them,'' said  
Valhol's owner, James Jackson, who has raced claiming horses for 
years. ``It's breathtaking.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Racing for only the third time, all this year, Valhol won the  
Arkansas Derby by 4 1-2 lengths over Certain and paid a winning 
mutuel of $62,80. Torrid Sand finished third in a field of seven 
3-year-olds. 
</P>
<P>
	Pat Day, who had ridden Cat Thief and Arkansas Derby and Answer  
Lively, fifth in the Arkansas Derby, dodged a lot of 
second-guessing for his decision to ride Menifee. 
</P>
<P>
	Although it was the colt's fourth victory in five career starts,  
he had finished second in the Tampa Bay Derby in his previous 
start. 
</P>
<P>
	About his choice to ride Menifee ($17.40) in his 1 1-4-length  
victory over Cat Thief, Day said, ``When it was all said and done, 
we thought this horse had a lot of room for improvement.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``He made the choice to go with Menifee,'' Arthur Hancock III,  
breeder and co-owner of Menifee, said of Day's decision. ``Good 
choice, Pat.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Adonis ($8.40) ran the fourth fastest Wood Memorial, covering 1  
1-8 miles in 1:47 3-5, two-fifths of second off the stakes record. 
</P>
<P>
	``I always knew Adonis was a good horse,'' owner Ernie Paragallo  
said. ``Adonis is bred to run a mile and a quarter or a mile and a 
half (the distance of the Belmont Stakes).'' 
</P>
<P>
	Adonis, wearing blinkers for the first time at the suggestion of  
jockey Jorge Chavez, won the Wood by two lengths over Best of Luck 
for his third victory in his last four races. Cliquot finished 
third in the 11-horse field. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
