<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Zimmer Says Retirement is Option </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Hobbling through the dugout using a fungo bat as  
a cane, Don Zimmer insisted he was serious: He will walk away from 
a half-century in baseball if his bum right knee does not get 
better. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would do it,'' the New York Yankees interim manager said  
before Sunday's 11-2 win over Detroit. ``This is no fun.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Zimmer, 68, returned this year for his fourth straight season as  
manager Joe Torre's bench coach. He had arthroscopic surgery in 
early March to repair torn cartilage, but the pain is still so bad 
that he's considering retirement. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've never gone through anything like this,'' he said. ``I've  
got to think about something else.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Zimmer was hoping a cortisone shot would ease the discomfort,  
though he admitted that might help for only 10 days or so. As it 
is, he's been taking Tylenol on a daily basis. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every day I wake up and think it's going to get better, and it  
doesn't get any better,'' he said. ``If I have to have a new knee, 
a plastic knee, I'd do it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Zimmer said only his loyalty to Torre and the Yankees has kept  
him in place. He became manager after Torre was diagnosed with 
prostate cancer in mid-March, and is certain his knee did not have 
time to heal before he took over. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was asked to do a job,'' Zimmer said. ``Somebody has to make  
decisions, and Joe wanted me to do it. George (Steinbrenner) wanted 
me to do it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Torre had surgery last month, and hopes to return by early May.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not coming back if he's going to retire,'' Torre joked  
Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	In the meantime, Zimmer has been limping around. He no longer  
watches batting practice from behind second base, as he likes to 
do, because it's too hard to get out there and back. 
</P>
<P>
	Zimmer has been part of the baseball scene since he began  
playing pro ball in 1949. A former All-Star infielder, coach and 
manager, Popeye has been all over the majors and minors. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet even with the World Series champions off to a 5-1 start and  
looking as strong as ever, Zimmer is adamant that he would leave if 
the pain does not go away. 
</P>
<P>
	And remember, Zimmer has simply called it quits before.  
</P>
<P>
	On June 6, 1995, while he was a bench coach for the Colorado  
Rockies, he snuck up behind manager Don Baylor in the fifth inning 
of a game against St. Louis, whispered ``Good luck the rest of the 
way,'' and walked out of Coors Field into retirement. 
</P>
<P>
	Late that year, Torre asked him to be the Yankees' bench coach  
and Zimmer eagerly accepted. His bad knee, though, has him thinking 
this could be the end. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know what I'd do, but I can't go on like this,'' he  
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
