<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> United States 3, Cameroon 1 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BAUCHI, Nigeria (AP) -- The United States, behind two goals from  
Taylor Twellman, beat Cameroon 3-1 on today to advance to the 
second round of the FIFA World Youth Championship. 
</P>
<P>
	Carlos Bocanegra had the other goal for the Americans, who play  
Spain on Thursday in the second round. 
</P>
<P>
	``Many people are shocked by how well we have played, but we  
haven't shocked ourselves,'' midfielder Steve Cherundolo said. ``We 
know we are a good team and today we proved it by beating a another 
very good team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The United States finished with six points in Group E, as did  
Japan and Cameroon, all with 2-1 records in the Under-20 
tournament. With the tie broken by goal difference, Japan finished 
first, the Americans second and Cameroon third. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's nice to sit back and watch your team when they are  
playing well,'' U.S. coach Sigi Schmid said. ``Today we played 
well, and tomorrow we'll go back to work so we'll play well in the 
second round.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Americans opened the scoring in the 39th minute. Twelman,  
with only goalkeeper Bayiha Ndjama to beat, took a pass from Lee 
Morrison and fired in a low shot from 12 yards. 
</P>
<P>
	In the 58th minute, Bocanegra scored on a header. Francisco  
Gomez lobbed a free kick from the right edge of the penalty area, 
and Nick Garcia headed it to Bocanegra. 
</P>
<P>
	Cameroon scored in the 64th minute when Francis Kioyo drove a  
free kick from just inside the area through the defensive wall and 
beneath diving goalkeeper Tim Howard. 
</P>
<P>
	Twellman sealed the victory in the 80th minute when he burst  
into the box and shot past Ndjama. 
</P>
<P>
	``They were big and physical, as you can see from his ice bag on  
my head,'' Twellman said. ``We knew this going into the game, and 
dealt with it very well, I thought.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Twenty-four teams divided into six groups started the 52-game  
tournament on April 3. The final is April 24 in Lagos. 
</P>
<P>
	Nigerian fans and riot police using whips or bamboolike canes  
clashed overnight in Lagos following Nigeria's 2-1 loss to 
Paraguay, it was reported Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Nigerian coach Tunde Disu was fired within an hour after the  
game and received a police escort when leaving the stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	Violence was reported in several areas of the sprawling port  
city throughout the night, the newspaper Thisday said. There were 
no reports of arrests or details on the number injured. 
</P>
</TEXT>
