<HEADLINE> Indians Opener Big Day for Alomars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- Only Albert Belle has been booed louder at  
Jacobs Field than Robbie Alomar. 
</P>
<P>
	Alomar, however, will never again have to feel the wrath of  
Cleveland fans like he did during the 1996 AL playoffs when they 
taunted him for spitting at umpire John Hirschbeck. 
</P>
<P>
	No longer an Oriole or a villain, Alomar is with the Indians  
now, and when he's introduced as Cleveland's new second baseman 
Monday at the home opener, he won't hear a single negative peep. 
</P>
<P>
	``The fans in Cleveland are really faithful to their team and  
they have knowledge about the other team,'' Alomar said Sunday in 
Minnesota before the Indians won their fifth straight, 9-8 over the 
Twins. ``Whenever I played there I understood that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Indians' 1999 home opener against Kansas City won't be much  
different from opening day '96, '97 or '98. Jacobs Field, sold out 
for all 81 home dates again this season, will be packed for the 
293rd straight time. And for the fourth straight year a flag 
celebrating an AL Central division title will be raised before the 
first pitch. 
</P>
<P>
	But Alomar makes this year's opener a special one -- for the  
Alomars and the Indians. 
</P>
<P>
	For the first time since they played together for the San Diego  
Padres in 1989, Robbie and his brother, Indians' catcher Sandy 
Alomar, are teammates once again. When they take their positions in 
the field before the top of the first Monday, their father, Sandy 
Sr., will be in the crowd watching his boys on the same team again. 
</P>
<P>
	``Opening day at home is another chance to play with my brother,  
on the same team and on the same home field,'' Robbie Alomar said. 
``It's going to be special.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Robbie Alomar's addition gives the Indians a lineup comparable  
to the World Series champion New York Yankees and has Cleveland 
fans believing they will get their first World Series title since 
1948. 
</P>
<P>
	After six games, it's easy to see what all the excitement is  
about. The Indians are coming home on a tear, having gone 5-1 on 
their season-opening road trip. Their three-game sweep this weekend 
in Minnesota was their first there since 1986. 
</P>
<P>
	They're averaging 9.7 runs per game and lead the AL in virtually  
every offensive category. Of the six starters to face them thus far 
this season, not one has gone beyond 4 1-3 innings. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's got to be a little discouraging for an opposing pitcher  
to look at our lineup before a game,'' Richie Sexson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Dave Burba, who using a nasty splitter struck out 10 in just six  
innings against Anaheim last week, will start the opener for 
Cleveland against Kansas City left-hander Jose Rosada. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm thrilled,'' Burba said. ``It's nice to get that  
assignment. It'll be a first for me. I'll be excited, but I'll be 
nervous too.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Burba missed a chance to pitch Cincinnati's home opener last  
season when he was traded by the Reds -- the team he grew up rooting 
for -- to the Indians the night before. He's not worried about a 
similar fate this year. 
</P>
<P>
	``Last year is forgotten,'' he said. ``I'm not looking at this  
start as a makeup for last year. It was just a coincidence, one of 
those things that happens in baseball. I think people made too much 
of my being upset. I don't even think about it anymore.'' 
</P>
<P>
 *Notes:* Former Indians pitcher and longtime broadcaster Herb Score,  
seriously injured in a near-fatal car accident last October, will 
throw out the ceremonial first pitch. ... For the second straight 
year, Native American protesters will demonstrate against the 
Indians use of their Chief Wahoo mascot outside the ballpark. Five 
were arrested last season when they attempted to burn Chief Wahoo 
in effigy. Last Friday, those protesters filed a lawsuit against 
Cleveland police claiming their civil rights were violated. ... The 
Royals went 5-1 against the Indians in spring training. ... David 
Justice hasn't played since straining his left calf muscle in the 
season opener. ... Cleveland shortstop Omar Vizquel, who sat out 
Sunday's game with a sore quadriceps, has No. 14 written on his cap 
in honor of fellow Venezuelan Andres Galarraga. Galarraga is being 
treated for cancer and is expected to miss the year for Atlanta. 
``He's the Big Cat and I'm the Little Cat,'' Vizquel said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
