<HEADLINE> Garciaparra in As Pinch Hitter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. (AP) -- Boston's Nomar Garciaparra, resting  
a strained left hamstring for the fourth straight game, struck out 
as a pinch hitter in the ninth inning of today's 5-4 loss to the 
Tampa Bay Devil Rays. 
</P>
<P>
	Garciaparra hadn't played since Wednesday night's victory over  
Kansas City. But with two outs and one on, he batted against Devil 
Rays closer Roberto Hernandez. 
</P>
<P>
	The Red Sox, who rallied from a 4-0 deficit to tie the game, had  
fallen behind in the eighth on Danny Calyburn's solo homer off 
Derek Lowe. 
</P>
<P>
	The shortstop may return to the starting lineup as soon as  
Tuesday's home opener against the Chicago White Sox. He didn't 
second-guess manager Jimy Williams' decision to use him in the 
ninth. 
</P>
<P>
	``He asked if the opportunity presents itself, could I swing the  
bat? I said sure. I tried to go out there and do a job, try to pick 
the team up. I didn't do it,'' Garciaparra said. 
</P>
<P>
	``For me, it was the right thing to do,'' Williams said. ``Hey,  
we're down one run. I sent up a very good hitter. It just didn't 
work.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
