<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Recounting Lincoln's Murder </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- In the most chilling moment of his crowded  
evening, correspondent Lawrence Gobright walked into the 
flag-draped box at Ford's Theatre and took charge of the pistol 
used by John Wilkes Booth to shoot Abraham Lincoln. 
</P>
<P>
	``A man standing by picked up Booth's pistol from the ground,''  
Gobright recalled. ``I exclaimed to the crowd below that the weapon 
had been found and placed in my possession.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A Navy officer demanded it. Gobright refused and held the .44  
caliber, silver-mounted derringer for the police. 
</P>
<P>
	The reporter examined the carpeted presidential box, observed  
the darkening blood on the buttoned back of Lincoln's rocking 
chair, noted the rip in the Treasury flag that draped the railing. 
Later investigation showed it had been made by Booth's spur as he 
leaped to the stage and escaped. 
</P>
<P>
	Just minutes before, Gobright had been alone at the office of  
The Associated Press on Pennsylvania Avenue, leafing through a 
newspaper. An excited friend burst through the door shouting ``that 
the president had been assassinated.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The story tumbled out. The friend had been in the audience at  
Ford's. A gunshot was heard over the roar of a laugh line in the 
third act of the comedy, ``Our American Cousin.'' The president 
slumped forward. Mary Lincoln screamed. 
</P>
<P>
	Gobright got the gist of the story, ran into the telegraph  
office and filed ``a short special'' that is still quoted as a 
model of terse story-telling. 
</P>
<P>
	``WASHINGTON, Friday, April 14, 1865. The President was shot in  
a theater to-night, and is perhaps mortally wounded.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A Pennsylvania native, Lawrence Agustus Gobright took his first  
Washington newspaper job in 1834 during Andrew Jackson's 
administration. The AP hired him shortly after its founding in 
1848. 
</P>
<P>
	During the Civil War, Gobright reported the maneuvers of the  
politicians and the ``gunpowder news'' of battles. He had wrestled 
with the official censor, once having to water down an account of a 
Confederate invasion of Maryland even though his story was clearly 
no news to the invaders. 
</P>
<P>
	But early in the war, other reporters complained that the censor  
waved Gobright's stories through while spiking theirs. 
</P>
<P>
	Summoned before the House Judiciary Committee, Gobright gave  
what has been called one of the first descriptions of objective 
news writing. He volunteered that the news service's practical 
determination to be factual, non-political and impartial might have 
given it an edge. 
</P>
<P>
	``My dispatches are merely dry matters of fact and detail,''  
Gobright testified. ``Some special correspondents may write to suit 
the temper of their own organs. ... I try to write without regard 
to men or politics.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Over four years Gobright had come to know Lincoln well.  
</P>
<P>
	He had often witnessed the president's determination never to be  
bested in the telling of a funny story. But he had also seen an 
agitated Lincoln in the Army telegraph office, his face ``ghastly'' 
in the gas light, his hands and legs shaking, his mournful voice 
repeating, ``bad news, bad news.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But the second week of April 1865 was jubilation time. Lee  
surrendered his army to Grant on Sunday the 9th. Lincoln had been 
thronged by freed slaves while visiting Richmond. Gobright had seen 
him at the White House on the 10th proposing the band play the 
Confederacy's ``Dixie'' because ``we have lawfully captured it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Now Lincoln lay lengthwise on a boarding house bed across 10th  
Street from the theater, unconscious, his breath labored, doctors 
shaking their heads at the somber Cabinet members crowding the 
small room. Gobright sped around town, also picking up details of 
the attempted assassination of Secretary of State William H. 
Seward, and returned to his office to tell the fuller story. 
</P>
<P>
	``With trembling and nervous fingers,'' he began to write, in  
chronological order as dictated by the style of the day. He did not 
mention the gunshot until the second sentence of the third 
paragraph. 
</P>
<P>
	Then, sentence after sentence, it was all business: the mortal  
wound in the back of the president's head, the flight of the 
still-unknown assassin, the attack on Seward, the ``wild 
excitement,'' the evidence of ``a preconcerted plan.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I was afterwards surprised that I had succeeded in  
approximating so closely all the facts in those dark 
transactions,'' he wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE: Lawrence L. Knutson has reported on Congress, the  
White House and Washington's history for more than 30 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
