<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Lower in Early Tokyo Trading / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The dollar was lower against the yen in early  
trading Monday as the greenback faced selling from overseas 
investors. Prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange edged lower. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 120.52 yen in early trading, down 0.44 yen  
from late Friday in Tokyo and also below its late Friday level of 
120.98 yen in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average fell 163.55 points,  
or 0.97 percent, to 16,692.08 in the first 30 minutes of trading. 
On Friday, the index gained 8.94 points, or 0.05 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, Japanese exporters sold the dollar above  
121 yen, while Japanese trust banks and importers were buying the 
currency at the low 120-yen level, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	Japanese investors largely ignored the results of the Tokyo  
gubernatorial election Sunday, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	Shintaro Ishihara, a former transport minister and controversial  
author known for his hawkish, nationalistic views, won the vote in 
a landslide. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 130.70 yen in early  
trading, down from 130.43 yen late Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, prices fell as players took profits,  
traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	High-technology and blue-chip shares, including Sony Corp.,  
Toshiba Corp. and NEC, were mostly lower on worries about earnings 
outlooks. 
</P>
<P>
	Those concerns were fueled in part by Compaq Computer's warning  
Friday in the United States that first-quarter earnings would fall 
below analysts' estimates, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors were also concerned that New York share prices may be  
struggling to maintain their strength, said Yoshiyuki Higashi, 
manager of investment information at Taiheiyo Securities. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section was down 12.76 points, or 0.95 percent, to 1,330.15. 
The TOPIX fell 2.16 points, or 0.16 percent, Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark No. 211 10-year Japanese government  
bond was unquoted early Monday. It finished Friday at 1.610 percent 
and was priced at 101.66 yen. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
