<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	A storm system spread rain and snow across the Great Lakes on  
Sunday and pushed a line of showers and thunderstorms across the 
Middle Atlantic States. 
</P>
<P>
	Rain stretched from Wisconsin across Michigan into Canada.  
</P>
<P>
	Temperatures were low enough to change the rain to snow across  
far northern sections of Wisconsin and Michigan, with up to 5 
inches of snow falling overnight in parts of Michigan. 
</P>
<P>
	A cold front extending from the heart of the storm curved  
through upstate New York and Pennsylvania and southwestward along 
the Appalachians. Hail more than a half-inch in diameter was 
reported near Westmoreland, Pa., the National Weather Service said. 
</P>
<P>
	As that line pushed eastward, showers and scattered  
thunderstorms spread through the Appalachians into North Carolina, 
Virginia, Maryland, Delaware and New Jersey. 
</P>
<P>
	In the West, a second storm system spread light to moderate rain  
over parts of California. 
</P>
<P>
	The rain changed to snow in the Trinity Mountains of northern  
California, the Sierra Nevada and some mountains around the Los 
Angeles area. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere, a few, light, isolated showers and thundershowers  
developed over Texas and from Alabama into northern Georgia. 
</P>
<P>
	Sunday's temperatures around the Lower 48 ranged from a morning  
low of 9 below zero at Yellowstone National Park to an early 
afternoon reading of 85 at Pompano Beach, Fla. The lowest wind 
chill was 9 below at Yellowstone in Wyoming. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
