<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Olazabal Credits Doctor at Masters  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AUGUSTA, Ga. (AP) -- After winning the Masters on Sunday, Jose  
Maria Olazabal wanted to share it with the German doctor who saved 
his career. 
</P>
<P>
	Olazabal, who captured his second green jacket with a two-stroke  
victory over Davis Love III, was out of golf for 18 months because 
of foot problems that were mistakenly diagnosed as rheumatoid 
arthritis. 
</P>
<P>
	The pain already was apparent when Olazabal won his first  
Masters in 1994. It became unbearable near the end of the following 
year, and he didn't pick up a club in '96 -- often confined to a 
sofa at his Spanish home. 
</P>
<P>
	Olazabal feared he wouldn't be able to walk again, much less  
play golf. That year, he watched the Masters on television. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was not very pleasant, watching the rest of the players  
playing the Masters, knowing you have a right to be here and not 
being able to play,'' he said. ``That made it really hard.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Finally, while in Germany to be fitted for a special shoe, he  
was treated by Dr. Hans-Wilhelm Muller-Wohlfahrt. The doctor told 
Olazabal the problem wasn't in his feet, prescribing a painful 
exercise program and injections for his lower back. 
</P>
<P>
	As it turned out, the problem was caused by two faulty  
vertebrae, which were pinching nerves affecting his feet. Soon, the 
pain began to subside, and Olazabal returned to golf in the spring 
of '97 at a tournament in Dubai. 
</P>
<P>
	On Sunday, Olazabal thanked the doctor who cured his foot  
problem. 
</P>
<P>
	``Without him, I wouldn't be standing here,'' he said. ``I think  
I won this tournament because of him. He did a wonderful job with 
me, and I want to thank him from here. 
</P>
<P>
	``I will thank him personally because I think this victory, part  
of it, belongs to him, too.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
