<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 1999 Bristol Road Rage at Minimum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRISTOL, Tenn. (AP) -- Bristol Motor Speedway's reputation for  
producing an abundance of scrap metal was the main topic at the 
drivers' meeting held 90 minutes before the start of today's Food 
City 500. 
</P>
<P>
	``We know this is a tight track. We know there's going to be  
some bumping and grinding,'' NASCAR events director David Hoots 
told the drivers. ``But we also have a penalty box. We've got this 
old penalty box, and we'll use it if we have to.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Several drivers were involved in repeated incidents, including  
Kenny Irwin, Jerry Nadeau and Dick Trickle, but no one was sent to 
the penalty box. The only sanction involved Ricky Craven, who was 
held in the pits briefly for exceeding the pit-road speed of 35 mph 
while coming in to get his wrecked car repaired. 
</P>
<P>
	The most serious crash occurred when Nadeau cut down in front of  
Bobby Labonte, setting off a chain-reaction wreck behind them that 
significantly damaged the cars of several contenders, including 
Tony Stewart. 
</P>
<P>
	``The guy who caused half the yellows finally took us out,''  
Stewart said of Nadeau. ``He was bound and determined he was going 
to crash some good cars, and he did.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nadeau, who was three laps down at the time, wasn't about to  
accept complete responsibility for the incident. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was going by a lapped car, Bobby Labonte, and it looked like  
he was pushing real bad,'' Nadeau said. ``I might not have given 
him enough room, or he might have pushed into me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Television replays appeared to show Labonte holding his line and  
Nadeau turning in front of him. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were just a victim of circumstance,'' Labonte said.  
</P>
<P>
	The race was slowed by seven caution flags for 57 laps, limiting  
Rusty Wallace's average winning speed to 93.363 mph. 
</P>
<P>
	No injuries were reported in any of the wrecks.  
</P>
<P>
                              *------	 
</P>
<P>
	FRESH DRIVER: Kyle Petty, who finished eighth, tried to make  
light of the fact that he had failed to qualify for two of the six 
previous races this season -- including the most recent event two 
weeks ago in Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	``We weren't surprised we ran well,'' said Petty, one of nine  
drivers who wound up on the lead lap. ``You've got to remember, 
I've missed two races this year, so I've been rested up for 
Bristol.'' 
</P>
<P>
                              *------	 
</P>
<P>
	SPENCER'S PAIN: Jimmy Spencer, still smarting from rib injuries  
suffered in a late-race crash at Texas, made it halfway through the 
Bristol race before giving way to relief driver Steve Grissom. 
</P>
<P>
	Spencer radioed to his team that he was ``hurting everywhere,''  
and when he pitted under caution on lap 252 he needed assistance to 
get out of his car. He was placed in a waiting golf cart and driven 
to the infield care center, where he was examined and released. 
</P>
<P>
                              *------	 
</P>
<P>
	BLAST FROM THE PAST: Stewart, who started fourth and led for 55  
laps, was trying to become the first Winston Cup rookie to win at 
Bristol since 1979. 
</P>
<P>
	The victorious rookie driver that year? Some guy named Dale  
Earnhardt, who went on to win another 70 races, not to mention 
seven Winston Cup championships. 
</P>
<P>
                              *------	 
</P>
<P>
	DALE'S DAY: Speaking of The Intimidator, Earnhardt started last  
on the 43-car grid Sunday because he crashed his primary car in 
Saturday's final practice session and had to switch to a backup. 
</P>
<P>
	Earnhardt steadily worked his way through the pack and spent the  
last half of the race running as high as sixth. He wound up 10th, 
the last car on the lead lap. 
</P>
<P>
	``We only got about 15 laps of practice on that backup car, and  
the crew really did a great job getting it ready,'' he said. ``My 
hat's off to them.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
