<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Launch High-Tech Biz in US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Six years ago Hideaki Morishita turned his  
back on a secure but frustrating job with Japanese 
telecommunications giant NTT Corp. and struck out for America with 
a dream of launching an Internet business. 
</P>
<P>
	Morishita's experiment in personal initiative is paying off. His  
M.M. Systems, based in suburban Torrance, builds Web sites for a 
growing clientele of companies doing business in Japan or among 
Japanese expatriates in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	``In Japan it's, 'You have to do this, you have to do that,' ''  
Morishita said. ``I can do what I want to here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	What was a bold and radical step when Morishita made his move in  
1993 is becoming more common as Japan struggles with recession and 
record-high unemployment. 
</P>
<P>
	No agency keeps statistics, but observers say an increasing  
number of young entrepreneurs frustrated by Japan's slow-moving 
business culture are forsaking their homeland to seek their 
fortunes in America's high-tech marketplace. 
</P>
<P>
	A more fundamental shift is taking place as well. Japanese  
corporations are studying the business model that emerged from 
Silicon Valley during the late 1980s in which small, flexible 
companies often rise quickly based on the ability to rapidly 
develop and market new technologies. 
</P>
<P>
	The trend marks a sharp change from the 1980s, when U.S.  
businesses scrambled to emulate their Japanese counterparts. 
Momentum shifted eastward across the Pacific during the 1990s as 
U.S. companies took the lead in quickly developing new computer 
software and Internet technologies while Japan's economy began to 
struggle. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the '80s, studying Japanese management was very popular for  
Americans. It's totally different now. It's more Japanese 
professors and scholars coming to the U.S. to study the Silicon 
Valley entrepreneurial spirit,'' said Junko Matsubara, a manager of 
business development for Mitsubishi International, an arm of the 
Japanese conglomerate Mitsubishi Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	Indications of change are evident on both sides of the ocean.  
</P>
<P>
	At a recent conference in Los Angeles, the Japan External Trade  
Organization brought dozens of U.S. and Japanese companies together 
to strike deals and cross-pollinate with new ideas. In Northern 
California, Stanford University's US-Japan Technology Management 
Center and the International Business Incubator in San Jose perform 
similar functions. 
</P>
<P>
	In Japan some 40 corporations, including NTT, the Japan  
Development Bank and Toshiba Corp., are members of Smart Valley 
Japan, a 400-member group created to foster the entrepreneurial 
spirit. The group is patterned after Smart Valley Inc., a Silicon 
Valley booster group formed during the recession of the early 
1990s. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's definitely a trend toward more entrepreneurship, more  
startups in Japan,'' said Richard Dasher, director of the US-Japan 
Technology Management Center. ``There's a great deal of interest in 
the model. Many people are coming here to find out how the model 
works.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The challenge is to apply it in a way that fits Japanese culture  
and sensibilities. Some of the very elements that have made the 
high-tech U.S. entrepreneurship successful -- fast-forming alliances 
and quick movement to markets -- clash with the Japanese business 
tradition of careful, deliberate planning. 
</P>
<P>
	In the meantime, young entrepreneurs such as Morishita are  
seeking their fortunes in the United States. In Japan, 
incorporating a new business costs $80,000 or more, and companies 
are slow to do business with newcomers. The requirement was 
intended to prevent fly-by-night companies that prey on consumers. 
But the law also has become a barrier to the creation of small 
business. 
</P>
<P>
	In California, Morishita was able to incorporate M.M. Systems  
for $4,300, including fees and attorney costs. Businesses seeking 
bilingual Web sites came to him looking for help, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Moreover, the Internet is far more accessible in the United  
States.	   A basic connection that costs $20 per month in the United States 
runs $100 or more monthly, plus per-minute connection charges, in 
Japan. Businesses and consumers alike have been slow to embrace the 
new medium, said Akira Tsuruname, who left his Japanese employer 
more than two decades ago to start his own business consulting 
service, California Coordinator. Now he helps Japanese business 
owners get started in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the real capitalist country,'' he said. ``Japan is a  
capitalist country, but it is a little more socialized. Also, now 
we are going to an information society. All the structure for the 
information society is here in the USA, and its open.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
