<DOCNO> APW19990411.0072 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-11 18:32:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rockies Hope Opener Heats Up Bats </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- To a man, the Colorado Rockies were hoping that  
Coors Field will prove to be a cure for their quiet bats. 
</P>
<P>
	After experiencing a little bit of everything in the first week  
of the season -- all on the road -- the Rockies (2-4) were scheduled 
to play their home opener on Monday against San Diego, starting a 
nine-game homestand. 
</P>
<P>
	``We haven't been swinging the bats well,'' manager Jim Leyland  
said Sunday after the Rockies' game at Los Angeles was postponed by 
a steady rain. ``We need our offense to come alive.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Through six games, the Rockies are hitting .275 and have scored  
just 22 runs. On Saturday, they managed only three hits in a 2-0 
loss to Kevin Brown. They have hit only two homers, although both -- 
by Dante Bichette and Todd Helton -- have contributed to their two 
wins. 
</P>
<P>
	A particular weakness has been the No. 3 spot in the batting  
order, vacated by the injured Larry Walker. Fill-ins Lenny Harris, 
Angel Echevarria and Pat Watkins have, as starters in that slot, 
hit just .087 (2-for-23) and are hitless in the last 15 at-bats. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have a key player out of the lineup, but so do a lot of  
other teams,'' Leyland said. ``I'm not going to panic after six 
ballgames.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Walker, sidelined by a strained muscle in his rib cage, isn't  
eligible to come off the disabled list until Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Colorado's pitching has been unexpectedly solid. The staff's  
ERA, which generally hovers around 5.00, is 3.60. 
</P>
<P>
	``Five of our six starts have been good ones,'' Leyland said.  
</P>
<P>
	The Rockies clearly were eager to get home. After a final  
exhibition game in Arizona on April 1, they played an exhibition at 
Coors Field on April 3, then traveled to Monterrey, Mexico, for the 
season opener against San Diego on April 4. Two days later, they 
resumed the series with the Padres in San Diego. Then came three 
games against the Dodgers in unusually cold, blustery conditions. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've been traveling a lot in the last week or so,'' Leyland  
said. ``We're ready to go home.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bichette agreed.  
</P>
<P>
	``Fifty-thousand every night -- it's a great place to play,'' he  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Vinny Castilla said Colorado fans ``are hungry for baseball.  
We're excited about going home.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pedro Astacio (0-1), scheduled to pitch for Colorado on Sunday,  
will take the mound on Monday instead. 
</P>
<P>
	``It won't bother me waiting a day,'' he said. ``I never had to  
warm up today, so it won't have any effect on me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Woody Williams (0-0) is scheduled to oppose him.  
</P>
<P>
	Leyland remained one win short of the 1,000 mark in his major  
league managing career. Only three active managers -- Tony La Russa, 
Bobby Cox and Joe Torre -- have reached that plateau. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think about that, that's not important,'' said  
Leyland, who ranks 45th on baseball's career list. ``I'd have to 
think we're going to win another game somewhere along the line.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
