<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Center Studies Ideas on Food Safety </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LANSING, Mich. (AP) -- Possibly coming soon to a refrigerator  
near you: hot dogs covered with an edible film to prevent 
contamination from potentially deadly bacteria like listeria, 
salmonella and E. coli. 
</P>
<P>
	At least that's where Elliot Ryser, a professor at Michigan  
State University, hopes his research will lead sometime in the next 
five years. 
</P>
<P>
	``The idea with the film is to try to make something like a  
Teflon suit ... so if bacteria lands on a hot dog it's 
inactivated,'' Ryser says. 
</P>
<P>
	Ryser is one of three dozen scientists affiliated with the  
school's new National Food Safety and Toxicology Center. The 
center, which opened last year, draws researchers from many 
different disciplines to study the safety of the food supply. 
</P>
<P>
	``The reason this center exists is to get a holistic view,''  
says director Robert Hollingworth. ``You've got to have 
microbiologists, process control people who understand the 
processes and behavioral scientists who understand how people 
react.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The recent listeria outbreak traced back to the Zeeland-based  
Bil Mar Foods plant is only one example of potential food safety 
hazards, he says. 
</P>
<P>
	An estimated 9,000 Americans die and 33 million become ill from  
foodborne illness every year, according to the federal Centers for 
Disease Control and Prevention. It's difficult to find more exact 
numbers because food poisoning cases are not always diagnosed or 
reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Worldwide, the figures are estimated to be many times that,  
especially in developing countries. 
</P>
<P>
	``Because it's food, everyone's at risk, especially infants,  
children and the elderly,'' Hollingworth says. 
</P>
<P>
	No official cause of the Zeeland outbreak has been determined,  
although there's speculation it may be related to air conditioning 
units in the plant. The outbreak has been linked to 15 adult deaths 
and six miscarriages or stillbirths in 22 states, according to the 
CDC. 
</P>
<P>
	The study of food safety is nothing new. What is unique about  
Michigan State's approach is the way it brings together academics 
of different stripes under one roof, according to Dane Bernard of 
the National Food Processors Association, an industry trade group. 
</P>
<P>
	``Things can happen around the water cooler that you don't have  
an opportunity for if you are not working together,'' he says. ``An 
example would be DNA technology which has been important in 
medicine but is really now just making itself known in the field of 
microbiology,'' the study of microorganisms. 
</P>
<P>
	There are only a handful of similar centers around the country,  
most less than a decade old. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal government is also getting into the act. Last year,  
it announced plans for the Joint Institute on Food Safety Research, 
which is designed to get the most out of research dollars by 
encouraging cooperation between the government, schools and 
industry. 
</P>
<P>
	``We find that there's a lot of enthusiasm at the federal level  
for having collaborative researh projects going on across the 
country,'' says David Edmark, a spokesman for the Food Safety 
Consortium, which coordinates food safety research among the 
University of Arkansas, Kansas State and Iowa State. ``Anything 
that can give you more efficient use of your dollars.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The industry already spends hundreds of millions of dollars on  
research into food safety, including projects at universities, 
according to Bernard. At Michigan State alone, it accounts for at 
least a quarter of a million dollars in research funding. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to researchers like Ryser who work on understanding  
bacterial behavior and preventing food contamination, the Michigan 
State center also examines several other areas of food safety, 
including: 
</P>
<P>
	-- Toxicology. How pesticides and other pollutants affect food  
and the human body. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Social dimensions of food safety. How public perception, the  
media and policy affect food safety. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Genetic engineering. Ways of creating grains and other crops  
that are resistant to disease and, in some cases, herbicides. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Natural product chemistry. How some foods or spices may  
contain natural disease-fighting substances. 
</P>
<P>
	Up until recently, the primary focus in food safety was on  
sanitation -- keeping work and packaging areas clean. 
</P>
<P>
	But in the last few years, the federal government and industry  
have turned to scientific testing to monitor levels of microbial 
organisms, like listeria and E. coli, that authorities now know can 
cause food poisoning. 
</P>
<P>
	The trend toward importing food from countries with different  
agricultural and meat regulations complicates the task of keeping 
food safe. 
</P>
<P>
	There's also room for improvement in the way industry processes  
fruits, vegetables, fish, poultry and meat products, according to 
Les Bourquin, a Michigan State professor affiliated with the 
center. 
</P>
<P>
	But for now, Hollingworth says, there's still a lot of basic  
research to be done into how microorganisms, or as he calls them 
``bugs,'' contaminate food. 
</P>
<P>
	``You have to understand where the hazards are,'' Hollingworth  
says. ``We don't even understand how these bugs move around in the 
environment.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
