<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Seeks To Soften VIP Image </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WATERLOO, Iowa (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore got a bit of a  
surprise when he plunged into a crowd and paused to admire Sherri 
Leach's dog, Poopsie. 
</P>
<P>
	``She's got some puppies, do you want one?'' Leach asked.  
</P>
<P>
	``We've got two dogs now,'' Gore said as he retreated down the  
line of people waiting to greet him. 
</P>
<P>
	Within minutes, Gore was facing some tough questions from  
8-year-old Jake Powers, who demanded to know how teachers can 
survive when ``they only get paid $3 a day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Those were typical scenes for Gore and his wife, Tipper, during  
the vice president's latest campaign trip through Iowa. Gore has 
vowed to break through the trappings of his office and connect with 
voters on a grass-roots level. 
</P>
<P>
	His aides liken it to a national campaign for sheriff.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'm going to spend an enormous amount of time here in Iowa,  
going from town to town and talking with people one at a time and 
one family at a time and in small groups and in living rooms,'' 
Gore said in an interview with The Associated Press last week. 
</P>
<P>
	Iowa and other small states that open the political season  
traditionally demand that candidates campaign up close and 
personal, with activists expecting to meet contenders and quiz them 
on issues. 
</P>
<P>
	``Showing up in living rooms in Iowa is no different than  
running 1,000 points of television in California,'' said veteran 
Democratic strategist Phil Roeder. ``It's what people expect.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That can be a problem for candidates like Gore, who travels with  
a huge, traffic-snarling vice presidential entourage of security, 
staff and reporters. Unlike his rivals, it's not easy for Gore to 
drop into a coffee shop for a quiet chat. 
</P>
<P>
	``You walk into a cafe unannounced and you talk with everybody  
there, for as long as they want to talk,'' said former Democratic 
gubernatorial candidate Don Avenson. ``That's what people expect.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tucked safely inside ``the bubble,'' a euphemism for the phalanx  
of Secret Service agents, that isn't easy. 
</P>
<P>
	``People who talk into their sleeves are intimidating,'' Avenson  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Determined to show he can overcome that, Gore scheduled a series  
of ``house parties'' in Iowa and mingled with Democratic activists. 
He even spent a night at a farm. 
</P>
<P>
	The parties jam 40 to 60 carefully selected backers into an  
average-size house. Moving into one party, Gore shed his coat and 
worked his way patiently through the rooms, backslapping and 
schmoozing, posing for photo after photo. 
</P>
<P>
	Trying to counter his reputation for stiffness, Gore often mugs  
and jokes with activists. 
</P>
<P>
	``He has a great sense of humor,'' said Miriam Tyson of  
Waterloo. ``He loosens up and is able to joke about himself.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After working his way around the room for 20 minutes or so, Gore  
stakes out a corner where he delivers an abbreviated stump speech, 
focusing on schools and those left behind during the current 
economic boon. 
</P>
<P>
	The diner version is similar. Gore moves through the crowd  
shaking hands and slapping backs, all the while soliciting advice 
on what to eat. In Waterloo, it was tenderloin with pie. 
</P>
<P>
	Larry Lavenz beamed after getting a picture of his family giving  
Gore a big hug. ``This is what he needs to do,'' Lavenz said. ``If 
he spends the next 19 months doing this, he won't need all that 
money for television.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In 1988, then-Vice President George Bush faced some of the same  
problems as Gore. Rivals spent more time on retail politics, and 
Bush finished third in Iowa's caucuses. Gore's only announced rival 
for the Democratic nomination is former New Jersey Sen. Bill 
Bradley, who has considerably more freedom to meet and greet 
Iowans. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have looked very closely at what Bush did in 1987 and  
1988,'' said one Gore aide who requested anonymity. ``We will be 
doing the stuff you do if you are running for sheriff.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gore appears determined to overcome the logistical difficulties.  
</P>
<P>
	``It just requires a little foresight, that's all,'' he said.  
``If you put in the time to plan it out, you can do just about 
anything you want, to go into a crowded living room, spend a night 
at a farm, go to a diner and sit up at the counter where people are 
having lunch. You just need to plan it out well.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
