<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NATO Scatters Bombs Over Yugoslavia  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Orthodox Easter in Yugoslavia began  
earlier today with a series of NATO air strikes. Despite bad 
weather hampering what allies could do, bombs still rained down on 
Kosovo on the day Serbians celebrate Easter, according to local 
reports. Meanwhile, the number of refugees fleeing or driven out of 
Kosovo during the crisis has topped 500,000, a scale of human 
displacement not seen in Europe since World War II. The latest 
figures compiled by the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees 
estimate the exodus at 521,000 people, the vast majority of them 
ethnic Albanians. 

</P>
<P>
	Gov't Tests Skies for Millennium  
</P>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- The Federal Aviation Administration has passed a  
live test of its new fixes to correct the year 2000 computer bug. 
The test involved the forwarding of computer clocks at Denver 
International Airport to the hour of midnight Dec. 31, 1999. An air 
traffic controller and the pilot of an approaching FAA plane then 
held a conversation that safely bridged the gap of the new century. 
Officials say the computers were able to read the new year 
successfully. The year 2000 glitch stems from computers not being 
able to read the date properly, a problem some officials believe 
could disrupt air traffic. 

</P>
<P>
	India Tests Nuclear-Capable Missile  
</P>
<P>
	NEW DELHI, India (AP) -- Defying appeals from the United States  
to put its nuclear program on hold, India has tested an upgraded 
version of its intermediate-range missile. Information Minister 
Pramod Mahajan told a hastily summoned news conference that the 
Agni II ballistic missile was successfully launched at 10 a.m. 
local time (12:30 a.m. EDT). Indian news agencies quoted government 
officials as saying Pakistan was given advanced warning. The test 
comes after India conducted a series of underground nuclear 
explosions last year that prompted Pakistan to respond with tests 
of its own, raising international fears of a nuclear arms race 
between the two belligerent nations. 

</P>
<P>
	Gore Says Draft Won't Be Reinstated  
</P>
<P>
	WAUSAU, Wis. (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore told a Boy Scout  
yesterday there were no plans to reinstate the draft, despite the 
NATO bombing campaign in Yugoslavia. The draft question by 
14-year-old Joe Wiesneski, was the most pointed about the conflict 
in Kosovo posed to Gore at a campaign fund-raiser. ``There is very 
little support for moving away from the volunteer Army,'' Gore 
said. President Clinton has repeatedly said he had no plan to send 
ground troops to fight in Kosovo. 

</P>
<P>
	Welfare Rolls Fall Again  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton yesterday used the latest  
report of shrinking welfare rolls -- cut nearly in half since 1993 -- 
to prod Congress for child care, housing and transportation 
programs that he said will move even more welfare recipients into 
jobs. He also announced final regulations that give states greater 
leeway in using federal welfare grants to set up such programs 
themselves. Nationally, just over 7.6 million Americans were 
receiving public assistance at the end of December, down from 
almost 8 million at the end of September and 14.3 million in 1994. 

</P>
<P>
	Man Wins Fight Over Roasting Chicken  
</P>
<P>
	TAMPA, Fla. (AP) -- A man who said Perdue Farms Inc. betrayed a  
confidentiality agreement and stole his secret method of preparing 
roasted chicken was awarded $27 million by a jury. It is now up to 
a judge to decide how much the nation's third-largest poultry 
company must pay to Dennis P. Hook in punitive damages. The jury 
awarded the compensatory damages on Friday. Judge Robert H. Bonanno 
must also decide whether to halt Perdue's marketing and sale of 
TenderReady chicken Hook said Perdue's TenderReady chicken was 
based on his idea. 

</P>
<P>
	Skating Coach Faces Allegations  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Craig Maurizi, a former student and then a  
colleague of famed skating coach Richard Callaghan, has accused his 
former mentor of involving him in an inappropriate sexual 
relationship, The New York Times reported today. The newspaper 
quoted Maurizi, 36, as saying the sexual relationship began in 1981 
after Callaghan moved to Philadelphia to coach and Maurizi, then a 
student, followed. Callaghan, who coached Tara Lipinski to an 
Olympic gold medal and Todd Eldredge to five national titles and a 
world championship, resigned as director of skating for the Detroit 
Skating Club in March. 

</P>
<P>
	Two Groups To Submit Bids for A's  
</P>
<P>
	OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) -- Two investment groups will make bids to  
buy the Oakland Athletics this week, a team representative said. 
The groups will submit separate bids on a one-time offer to buy the 
franchise for $120 million, according to a representative of the 
Oakland-Alameda County Coliseum Authority in the potential sale. 
Local government officials are worried that the A's may move, 
possibly to San Jose. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAN BOYLAN  
</P>
</TEXT>
