<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopian Wins Cherry Blossom Run </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Two-time Olympian Worku Bikila of Ethiopia  
endured a steady downpour today to win the 10-mile Cherry Blossom 
Run in 46 minutes, 59 seconds. 
</P>
<P>
	Bikila withstood a late charge from Kenyans Lazarus Nyakeraka  
and James Kariuki. Nyakeraka finished two seconds behind the 
winner, with Nariuki another two seconds back in third. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was all about who could last the longest,'' Bikila said.  
``The conditons made it very tough to stay ahead.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The rain and chilly temperatures were so uncomfortable for the  
runners that a postrace awards ceremony was canceled for fear of 
hypothermia. 
</P>
<P>
	Kenyans dominated the men's competition, placing 12 among the  
top 14 finishers. Eric Morrison of Lakewood, Colo., was the top 
American, finishing 15th. 
</P>
<P>
	Jane Omoro won the women's race at 53:37, one second ahead of  
Kenyan countrywoman Jane Ngotho. Six of the top 10 women's 
finishers were from Kenya. 
</P>
<P>
	Nnenna Lynch of Concord, Mass., led the American women,  
finishing ninth at 55:39. 
</P>
<P>
	Bikila and Omoro each won $5,000.  
</P>
<P>
	Bill Rodgers, bidding for a world record for runners over the  
age of 50, fell 1:11 short of the current mark of 52:53. Rodgers, 
51, placed 33rd overall among the 6,200 entrants in the race. 
</P>
</TEXT>
