<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Insurance Rises for Russia Airlines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Several Russian insurance companies have hiked  
their rates for airlines because of potential problems caused by 
the year 2000 computer glitch. 
</P>
<P>
	The insurance companies are concerned that Russia's airlines --  
many of which are broke and have poor safety records -- haven't 
prepared their computers, Viktor Gorlov, deputy director of the 
Russian Federal Aviation Service, told the Interfax news agency. 
</P>
<P>
	The so-called ``Millennium Bug'' may wreak havoc if computers  
that only use two figures to designate a year misread the year 2000 
for 1900, and produce erroneous information. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia's government and businesses have been slow to tackle the  
problem because of more pressing issues -- including a severe cash 
shortage -- over the past few years. 
</P>
<P>
	But Gorlov said the insurance companies' fears were unfounded  
because the aviation service is ``doing everything possible'' to 
make sure the computer bug doesn't strike Russia's airlines. 
</P>
<P>
	Gorlov admitted, however, that the Federal Aviation Service  
won't be able to enforce testing of all the airlines' computer 
equipment. 
</P>
<P>
	``The budget does not allocate any resources for this,'' he  
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
