<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990411.0081 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-11 23:11:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S.: Milosevic Could Lose Power </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic has  
backed himself into a corner where loss of power and trial as a war 
criminal may be inevitable, Clinton administration and military 
officials say. 
</P>
<P>
	That grim depiction of Milosevic's future came as an  
increasingly assertive Congress returns from two weeks off to 
debate whether to sanction the use of ground troops to drive 
Serbian forces out of Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton and his aides have emphasized they will not  
negotiate with Milosevic, and the only way he can stop the NATO air 
strikes is to remove his troops from Kosovo, allow the refugees to 
return, give Kosovo autonomy and let in NATO peacekeeping troops. 
</P>
<P>
	On Sunday, administration officials toughened that stance. White  
House chief of staff John Podesta said on NBC's ``Meet the Press'' 
that Milosevic had started four wars in 10 years -- in Slovenia, 
Croatia, Bosnia and Kosovo -- and that Yugoslavia could not become a 
real member of the European community with him in power. 
</P>
<P>
	Ultimately, ``for them to create a stable situation, it looks to  
me like they are going to need a new leader,'' Podesta said. 
</P>
<P>
	Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, in Brussels for NATO  
talks, said that with Serbian attacks on ethnic Albanians in 
Kosovo, many elements of the peace settlement that the Kosovars 
accepted but Milosevic rejected last month ``have been overtaken by 
events.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott, on CBS' ``Face the  
Nation,'' said Milosevic would eventually be held responsible for 
his attacks on ethnic minorities. ``That means the International 
War Crimes Tribunal in The Hague,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked how the United States could negotiate with someone it  
considers a war criminal, Talbott replied: ``We're not negotiating 
with Milosevic, we're bombing him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Defense Secretary William Cohen, on ABC's ``This Week,'' said  
that while he couldn't confirm reports of a mass grave in Kosovo, 
``I suspect ... that we are going to find more and more evidence of 
mass graves, mass executions, some pretty horrific stories.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Military officials said the bombing was beginning to take a  
serious toll on the troops that have persecuted Albanian Kosovars 
and keep Milosevic in power. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to attack, degrade, disrupt and ultimately, if he  
doesn't comply to the demands of the international community, he is 
going to lose those forces.'' NATO's military commander, Army Gen. 
Wesley Clark, said on CNN's ``Late Edition.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gen. Henry Shelton, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, told  
ABC that the airstrikes had already begun to drive apart elements 
of Yugoslavia's 3rd Army, which is leading the attacks in Kosovo. 
He said the military and police were being hurt ``by the lack of 
fuel, the lack of ammunition, the lower morale as a result of now 
starting to be pounded by NATO air.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But that may not be enough for many members of Congress. Sens.  
Joseph Biden, D-Del., and John McCain, R-Ariz., agreed on NBC that 
Milosevic was a war criminal and that it was a mistake for the 
administration to state from the beginning that the use of ground 
troops in Kosovo was not an option. 
</P>
<P>
	McCain, who recently returned from a trip to the Balkans with  
Cohen, said he would seek a resolution giving the president the 
authority to use all means necessary, including ground troops, to 
achieve the stated goals in Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not achieving our objectives; (Milosevic is) achieving  
his,'' said McCain, a Republican presidential candidate. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton is to meet with congressional leaders tonight to discuss  
Kosovo, and hold a more extended meeting with members of Congress 
on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Cohen stressed that Clark and other NATO officials had not  
requested ground troops, but if that request came, plans could be 
drawn up fairly quickly. NATO last fall estimated that it could 
take up to several hundred thousand troops to overcome hostile 
Yugoslav troops in Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	Clark said the air campaign was working but ``has a long way to  
go.'' He noted that Yugoslav troops are ``battle-hardened'' and 
that Milosevic has committed only one-third of his military 
capability to the Kosovo operation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
