<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Torre, Yanks Get World Title Rings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Joe Torre took a couple of steps, jogged a few  
more and then broke into a full trot. 
</P>
<P>
	His World Series ring -- the one bearing the words ``Best Ever''  
and ``Tradition'' -- was waiting near the mound, and he was in a 
hurry to put it on. 
</P>
<P>
	``I anticipated walking out there, but the crowd started me  
running,'' the New York Yankees manager said Sunday. ``Building up 
to it was pretty emotional when you realize what it represents.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Torre was the last of the Yankees to receive his ring in  
ceremonies before an 11-2 romp over Detroit. 
</P>
<P>
	Back at the ballpark in uniform for the first time since surgery  
for prostate cancer in mid-March, Torre received a standing ovation 
from a crowd held down to 32, 398 by a gametime temperature of 44 
degrees. 
</P>
<P>
	Within minutes, he already had the new jewelry on the ring  
finger of his right hand, the place that used to occupy his 1996 
World Series prize. 
</P>
<P>
	The 14-carat gold ring features the interlocking ``NY'' set with  
24 diamonds, one for each of the Yankees' record championships. It 
was Torre's wish that it said ``Best Ever'' after a record 125 wins 
that included a Series sweep of the San Diego Padres. 
</P>
<P>
	``This shuts out '98,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Owner George Steinbrenner added his opinion, too -- he wanted an  
oval shape rather an square design, similar to the style Joe 
DiMaggio won and wore in the 1940s. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know a lot is made about the money players make,'' Torre  
said, showing off his shiny hardware, ``but it's the ring that 
really drives you.'' 
</P>
<P>
	AL president Gene Budig presented the rings from a table set up  
between the mound and plate. Most players ran out to receive them 
and walked back to the dugout admiring them. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was wonderful to get a ring. That's what everyone wants,''  
catcher Jorge Posada said. ``It doesn't happen to too many people 
that they get two rings in three years.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Among the Yankees who did not take part was Roger Clemens,  
acquired in a February trade with Toronto. The Rocket, who has 
never won a Series title, made sure he saw what all the fuss was 
about. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I came off the field, he was looking at the ring,'' Torre  
said. ``The look in his eyes wasn't envy, it was hunger.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Darryl Strawberry, rehabilitating at extend spring training, and  
Andy Pettitte, currently on the disabled list, came in person to 
collect their rings. General manager Brian Cashman, Don Zimmer and 
the coaching staff, the medical staff and clubhouse personnel were 
among those also taking part. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is what the team's all about,'' Torre said. ``We earned  
this ring. It was a team effort.'' 
</P>
<P>
	David Wells, Graeme Lloyd, Tim Raines and Homer Bush, part of  
the '98 club but now playing elsewhere, probably will get the rings 
when their teams visit Yankee Stadium later this season. 
</P>
<P>
	Torre, meanwhile, plans to wear his '98 ring all the time,  
though he'll also find plenty of time to sport his '96 version. 
</P>
<P>
	And if all goes well, Torre hopes to return to the Yankees as  
their full-time manager in 3-4 weeks. He's started to work out and 
says he feels fine, yet does not want to rush his health. 
</P>
<P>
	``The first of next month is a pretty good barometer,'' Torre  
said. ``My wife can sense that I need to get to the ballpark.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
