<DOCNO> APW19990411.0089 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-11 14:28:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Launch High-Tech Biz in US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Six years ago Hideaki Morishita turned his  
back on a secure but frustrating job with Japanese 
telecommunications giant NTT Corp. and struck out for America with 
a dream of launching an Internet business. 
</P>
<P>
	Morishita's experiment in personal initiative is paying off. His  
M.M. Systems, based in suburban Torrance, builds Web sites for a 
growing clientele of companies doing business in Japan or among 
Japanese expatriates in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	``In Japan it's, 'You have to do this, you have to do that,' ''  
Morishita said. ``I can do what I want to here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	What was a bold and radical step when Morishita made his move in  
1993 is becoming more common as Japan struggles with recession and 
record-high unemployment. 
</P>
<P>
	No agency keeps statistics, but observers say an increasing  
number of young entrepreneurs frustrated by Japan's slow-moving 
business culture are forsaking their homeland to seek their 
fortunes in America's high-tech marketplace. 
</P>
<P>
	A more fundamental shift is taking place as well. Japanese  
corporations are studying the business model that emerged from 
Silicon Valley during the late 1980s in which small, flexible 
companies often rise quickly based on the ability to rapidly 
develop and market new technologies. 
</P>
<P>
	The trend marks a sharp change from the 1980s, when U.S.  
businesses scrambled to emulate their Japanese counterparts. 
Momentum shifted eastward across the Pacific during the 1990s as 
U.S. companies took the lead in quickly developing new computer 
software and Internet technologies while Japan's economy began to 
struggle. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the '80s, studying Japanese management was very popular for  
Americans. It's totally different now. It's more Japanese 
professors and scholars coming to the U.S. to study the Silicon 
Valley entrepreneurial spirit,'' said Junko Matsubara, a manager of 
business development for Mitsubishi International, an arm of the 
Japanese conglomerate Mitsubishi Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	Indications of change are evident on both sides of the ocean.  
</P>
<P>
	At a recent conference in Los Angeles, the Japan External Trade  
Organization brought dozens of U.S. and Japanese companies together 
to strike deals and cross-pollinate with new ideas. In Northern 
California, Stanford University's US-Japan Technology Management 
Center and the International Business Incubator in San Jose perform 
similar functions. 
</P>
<P>
	In Japan some 40 corporations, including NTT, the Japan  
Development Bank and Toshiba Corp., are members of Smart Valley 
Japan, a 400-member group created to foster the entrepreneurial 
spirit. The group is patterned after Smart Valley Inc., a Silicon 
Valley booster group formed during the recession of the early 
1990s. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's definitely a trend toward more entrepreneurship, more  
startups in Japan,'' said Richard Dasher, director of the US-Japan 
Technology Management Center. ``There's a great deal of interest in 
the model. Many people are coming here to find out how the model 
works.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The challenge is to apply it in a way that fits Japanese culture  
and sensibilities. Some of the very elements that have made the 
high-tech U.S. entrepreneurship successful -- fast-forming alliances 
and quick movement to markets -- clash with the Japanese business 
tradition of careful, deliberate planning. 
</P>
<P>
	In the meantime, young entrepreneurs such as Morishita are  
seeking their fortunes in the United States. In Japan, 
incorporating a new business costs $80,000 or more, and companies 
are slow to do business with newcomers. The requirement was 
intended to prevent fly-by-night companies that prey on consumers. 
But the law also has become a barrier to the creation of small 
business. 
</P>
<P>
	In California, Morishita was able to incorporate M.M. Systems  
for $4,300, including fees and attorney costs. Businesses seeking 
bilingual Web sites came to him looking for help, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Moreover, the Internet is far more accessible in the United  
States.	   A basic connection that costs $20 per month in the United States 
runs $100 or more monthly, plus per-minute connection charges, in 
Japan. Businesses and consumers alike have been slow to embrace the 
new medium, said Akira Tsuruname, who left his Japanese employer 
more than two decades ago to start his own business consulting 
service, California Coordinator. Now he helps Japanese business 
owners get started in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the real capitalist country,'' he said. ``Japan is a  
capitalist country, but it is a little more socialized. Also, now 
we are going to an information society. All the structure for the 
information society is here in the USA, and its open.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990411.0090 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-11 14:25:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Panel: IOC Doing OK on Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- Members of an ethics panel that blistered the  
IOC last month for the Salt Lake bribery scandal gave a qualified 
endorsement today to the committee's efforts at reform. 
</P>
<P>
	Former Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell and members of his  
commission said the International Olympic Committee appeared to be 
on the right track but more time was needed to see if meaningful 
changes would be carried out. 
</P>
<P>
	They pointed to shifts in the selection of Olympic host cities,  
establishment of two panels to rebuild the IOC and oversee the 
behavior of its members, and the expulsion of six delegates as 
signs that the committee seemed committed to change. 
</P>
<P>
	``We never expected that reform would occur immediately with the  
totality we suggested it would occur,'' Mitchell said. ``But we 
hope and expect it will be meaningful.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mitchell and members of his panel will testify Wednesday at  
Senate Commerce Committee hearings on the Olympic scandal. Mitchell 
refused to say what he would tell the committee, although he said 
the federal law that governs Olympic sports in the United States 
``make congressional review of the Olympic matters proper.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In his March 1 report, Mitchell said the IOC had fostered ``a  
culture of improper gift-giving'' that led to the Salt Lake 
vote-buying scheme. The ethics panel said drastic change was 
needed, including accountability for IOC members and a public look 
at the committee's finances. 
</P>
<P>
	After commending the U.S. Olympic Committee for acting  
``promptly and decisively'' in adopting a smaller list of 
recommended changes and ``accepting its share of responsibility'' 
for the scandal, Mitchell said the IOC actions were at an ``interim 
stage.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But he said the international committee -- with some 100 members  
representing different cultures from around the globe -- should not 
be held to the same timetable for quick action. 
</P>
<P>
	``You've got to give people time to do things,'' the Maine  
Democrat said. ``While we commend the USOC for moving rapidly, we 
have to accept the fact that others move at a different pace.'' 
</P>
<P>
	More would be known, he said, after an IOC session in June hears  
from a reform commission including Henry Kissinger, Peter Ueberroth 
and USOC president Bill Hybl. 
</P>
<P>
	A member of Mitchell's panel, baseball union chief Donald Fehr,  
said it would be ``many months'' before the IOC's future was clear. 
</P>
<P>
	Fehr and two other ethics members, Roberta Cooper Ramo and Jeff  
Benz, said they, too, liked the IOC's initial reaction to the 
scandal and their panel's recommendations. 
</P>
<P>
	But Benz, a former figure skater who serves on the USOC's  
athletes advisory council, was dismayed that only six of the 24 
sets on the IOC 2000 reform panel had been filled, and that no 
athletes had been picked so far. 
</P>
<P>
	Fehr said he was disappointed that IOC president Juan Antonio  
Samaranch had declined an invitation to testify before the Senate 
hearing. 
</P>
<P>
	Ramo, an Albuquerque, N.M., lawyer, said she was hopeful that  
Samaranch would take this opportunity to ``change the IOC in a 
powerful, positive way'' and adopt a ``true legacy of reform that 
the whole world would applaud.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One of the few domestic recommendations of Mitchell's panel  
still in limbo is a request that the IOC be declared a public 
international organization, making bribery of its members subject 
to the Federal Corrupt Practices Act. Mitchell said he had been in 
contact with the White House about the request and that a meeting 
would be scheduled for further discussions. 
</P>
<P>
	Mitchell, whose independent inquiry was appointed by the USOC,  
addressed the committee's board of directors on the findings. As he 
and other commission members left the podium to a standing ovation, 
Robert Garff, chairman of the Salt Lake Organizing Committee, took 
the floor to issue a ``formal public apology to this group on 
behalf of Salt Lake City.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The actions of a few people caused the grief here,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	As it wrapped up two days of meetings dominated by the Salt Lake  
scandal, the USOC also: 
</P>
<P>
	-- adopted minor changes to drug rules that permit random tests  
of Olympic and Pan American team members up to 120 days before 
competition, a 30-day extension. Task force head Baaron Pittenger 
said the added time would make it easier to catch cheating during 
training, since users of performance enhancers often start to taper 
drug use 90 days before a meet. 
</P>
<P>
	-- heard a status report on the committee's $26 million program  
to produce more U.S. medals at the Olympics. The first year of the 
plan for winter sports, dubbed Podium, produced 17 medals and a 
record 55 top-10 finishes at world championships, according to Norm 
Bellingham, its director. The program's goal is 26 medals at the 
2002 Winter Games, double the record-tying 13 from last year's 
Nagano Winter Games. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990411.0091 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-11 11:42:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> QB Couch Works Out for Browns Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LEXINGTON, Ky. (AP) -- With Cleveland Browns coach Chris Palmer  
supervising a 115-pass workout, Tim Couch made his final bid Sunday 
to be the No. 1 pick in the NFL draft. 
</P>
<P>
	Afterward, Palmer pronounced himself satisfied with Couch's  
performance, but declined to say whether the Kentucky quarterback 
or Oregon quarterback Akili Smith had the edge with six days left 
before the draft. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would say they're neck and neck coming down the stretch,''  
Palmer said. 
</P>
<P>
	Cleveland also is considering selecting Texas running back Ricky  
Williams, the Heisman Trophy winner, or trading the top pick. 
</P>
<P>
	Couch's 90-minute morning workout was held at a field house  
adjacent to Kentucky's Commonwealth Stadium. In attendance were 
Cleveland owner Al Lerner, football operations director Dwight 
Clark, president Carmen Policy and about eight other members of the 
organization. 
</P>
<P>
	The workout was Couch's second for the Browns. On March 11, in a  
workout run by Couch and his agent, Tom Condon, he threw about 45 
passes for officials from Cleveland and several other NFL teams. 
</P>
<P>
	On Sunday, with Palmer running the show, Couch threw in all  
directions and at all distances, from a straight drop and while 
rolling out. He also stopped a third of the way through to run a 
pair of 40-yard dashes. The quarterback said he was timed in 4.8 
seconds and 4.9 seconds. 
</P>
<P>
	Couch rarely was asked to throw the ball deep downfield in  
Kentucky's offense, which emphasized short passes and screens, and 
his arm strength has been questioned by some pro scouts. The 
quarterback said he threw about 15 deep balls for the Browns on 
Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Palmer had said before the session that he wanted to see how  
Couch performed when he was tired. 
</P>
<P>
	``I did get winded,'' Couch said, showing off his sweat-soaked  
T-shirt. ``But I think my arm stayed in pretty good shape.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Condon said he thought he might have a sense of what the Browns  
will do with the top pick by early in the week, but Policy said the 
team probably will not make a final decision until hours before the 
draft. 
</P>
<P>
	The New Orleans Saints want to discuss a trade with the Browns  
that would bring them the No. 1 pick. Saints coach Mike Ditka 
recently said he was willing to trade all his 1999 draft picks to 
Cleveland for a chance at selecting Williams. 
</P>
<P>
	Policy said the offer is intriguing.  
</P>
<P>
	``If you can get that blockbuster trade that gives you a  
combination of picks, presently and in the future, that can really 
set you up for the next 12 years, I think that we'd be very, very 
foolish not to give serious consideration to that alternative,'' he 
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
