<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cards Honor Hall of Fame Player </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- There's more company for the once-solitary Stan  
Musial statue outside Busch Stadium, now that the St. Louis 
Cardinals have unveiled a likeness of Hall of Famer Red 
Schoendienst. 
</P>
<P>
	Schoendienst, 76, was honored today prior to the Cardinals-Reds  
game. He's been with the team for 51 years -- 15 as a player, 12 as 
manager, 20 as coach and the last four as special assistant to 
general manager Walt Jocketty. 
</P>
<P>
	The bronze statue catches Schoendienst in mid-air at second  
base, kicking up dust as he makes the pivot on a double play. He 
said the only thing lacking from the statue, which is taken from a 
1946 World Series photograph, is the body of Johnny Pesky sliding 
beneath him. 
</P>
<P>
	``They made me better looking,'' said Schoendienst, who also  
threw out the first pitch Sunday, with Musial on the receiving end. 
</P>
<P>
	Several fellow Cardinals Hall of Famers attended the ceremony  
along with about two thousand fans. Among the baseball dignitaries 
were Musial, Bob Gibson, Lou Brock, Whitey Herzog, Enos Slaughter, 
Marty Marion, Bob Forsch and Danny Cox. 
</P>
<P>
	``I like the statue, I like it a lot,'' said Cox, a pitcher for  
the Cardinals in the 1980s. ``It shows some ingenuity, some 
thought. Not just some guy standing with a bat in his hands.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Schoendienst statue follows the unveiling of a Gibson statue  
and a bust of broadcaster Jack Buck outside the stadium last year. 
Later this summer, the Cardinals plan to honor Brock and Slaughter 
in similar fashion. 
</P>
<P>
	In return, Schoendienst paid tribute to new Cardinals ownership  
that has not forgotten the team's past. Since the new group bought 
the team from Anheuser-Busch Cos. Inc. in 1996, the uniform numbers 
of Schoendienst (3), Smith (1), Slaughter (9) have been retired and 
Busch Stadium has been modernized. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're fixing up the ballpark and keeping this game going in  
St. Louis,'' Schoendienst said. ``It is outstanding, for them to do 
what they're doing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For years, Schoendienst has been a fungo machine for the  
Cardinals. He's backed off some lately, although he keeps as active 
as possible. 
</P>
<P>
	``I used to hit them for hours,'' he said. ``Not anymore. Buddy  
Bates, our clubhouse guy, said he was going to get me two fungo 
bats. He said you lean on one now and now you'll be leaning on two, 
as old as you are.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Schoendienst had a .289 career average with 2,449 hits, played  
in 10 All-Star games and tied or led the league in fielding seven 
times. He was inducted into the Hall of Fame in 1989. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
