<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Brother John Sellers    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Brother John Sellers, a blues and gospel singer  
who started his climb to fame at age 5, died March 27. He was 74. 
</P>
<P>
	Sellers performed regularly in the early 1960s at Folk City, a  
Greenwich Village nightclub where musicians including Bob Dylan, 
Paul Simon and Joan Baez sang early in their careers. 
</P>
<P>
	He was born in Clarksville, Miss., where he was inspired by  
street performers like Robert Johnson and Blind Lemon Jefferson. By 
age five, he had begun singing, dancing and playing the tambourine 
in church-organized tent shows. 
</P>
<P>
	Four years later gospel singer Mahalia Jackson saw Sellers  
perform, and brought the boy, whose parents had abandoned him, to 
Chicago with her. As Jackson's fame grew, they sometimes sang 
together, and Sellers occasionally filled in for her at concerts. 
</P>
<P>
	Sellers made two recordings for Vanguard Records' new jazz line  
in the mid-1950s, teaming up with musicians like Sonny Terry, 
Johnny Johns and Jo Jones. 
</P>
<P>
	It was during a Folk City performance in 1961 that choreographer  
Alvin Ailey noticed him. The two later collaborated on Ailey's 
``Blues Suite'' and ``Revelations.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sellers' final performance with the well-known Ailey company was  
in 1997. At his death, he was involved in litigation with the 
troupe over royalties and the copyright to ``Revelations,'' one of 
Ailey's most famous compositions. 

</P>
<P>
 *Robert Widman    	
</P>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- Robert Widman, a retired reporter with The  
Plain Dealer, died Friday of cancer. He was 68. 
</P>
<P>
	Widman worked at The Plain Dealer from 1967 to 1987. His work  
included a series of stories on the abusive treatment of prison 
inmates and coverage of a 1970 state loan scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	He worked at The (Elyria) Chronicle-Telegram and The (Upper  
Sandusky) Daily Chief-Union before joining The Plain Dealer. 
</P>
<P>
	He became an antiques dealer when he retired.  
</P>
<P>
	Survivors include his wife, four sons, two daughters, 14  
grandchildren, a great-grandchild, and a brother. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990411.0095 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-11 11:42:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rep. Lazio in Giuliani's Shadow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BINGHAMTON, N.Y. (AP) -- In the race for the U.S. Senate seat  
being vacated by Democrat Daniel Patrick Moynihan, Rep. Rick Lazio 
is best known as ``the other Republican.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The main Republican is, of course, New York City Mayor Rudolph  
Giuliani, who is considering a race that could pit him next year 
against first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	``The other Democrat,'' U.S. Rep. Nita Lowey, has said she would  
not run if Mrs. Clinton does. Neither Giuliani nor Mrs. Clinton 
have said yet whether they will run. 
</P>
<P>
	Lazio, however, has made no such pledge not to take on Giuliani  
in a GOP primary. 
</P>
<P>
	The four-term congressman from Long Island concedes he won't run  
if the state's top Republican, Gov. George Pataki, asks him not to, 
but he said both the governor and former GOP Sen. Alfonse D'Amato 
``have been very generous with their advice.'' The governor's 
advice, he said, has been ``helpful and constructive.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And with relations between Pataki and Giuliani still chilly --  
the mayor crossed party lines in 1994 to back then-Gov. Mario Cuomo 
over Pataki -- a number of other Republicans think Pataki may put 
his muscle as well as his advice behind Lazio. 
</P>
<P>
	Another key factor is that conservatives tend to control  
Republican primaries, even in New York, said Jay Severin, a veteran 
GOP political operative. 
</P>
<P>
	Noting that Giuliani supports homosexual rights and was against  
President Clinton's impeachment -- Lazio voted for impeachment -- 
Severin said GOP primary voters ``are not for the new brand of Rudy 
Republicanism.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Also, the Republicans have an elephant as a mascot. One of the  
elephant's characteristics is a long memory and a bad temper,'' 
Severin added. ``Rudy opposed Pataki and endorsed Cuomo ... (and) 
the people who remember that, who don't forget it and don't forgive 
it, are all the people who vote in a Republican primary.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Giuliani also is suffering fallout from the fatal shooting by  
New York City police of an unarmed African immigrant. A Quinnipiac 
College poll out last week found the mayor's job approval rating 
among city voters at the lowest level of his six-year tenure. 
</P>
<P>
	Lazio has been crisscrossing traditionally Republican upstate  
New York for several months, meeting with local party leaders. 
</P>
<P>
	``He represents a fresh, young leadership perspective for the  
Republican Party,'' Erie County GOP Chairman Robert Davis said. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's really a bright light,'' Joseph Laughney, Broome County's  
GOP chairman, said after meeting Lazio for the first time Thursday 
over lunch. ``He's got a certain freshness about him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lazio fits the state Republican GOP's preferred profile for  
statewide candidates almost to a T. He's Roman Catholic, from the 
politically crucial suburbs surrounding New York City, supports 
abortion rights and favors the death penalty. He is Italian on his 
father's side and Danish on his mother's. He looks younger than his 
41 years and already has more than $2 million in his campaign bank 
account. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, there is a matter of recognition.  
</P>
<P>
	``If you ask somebody in Los Angeles who the mayor of New York  
City is, there's a 50 percent chance they'd know,'' Laughney said. 
``If I went up and down the street and said, `Congressman Lazio,' 
no one would know him, even in Binghamton.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990411.0096 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-11 22:52:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Farm Workers Union Promotes Boycott / Farm Scene  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOLEDO, Ohio (AP) -- Raised in the potato and strawberry fields  
of northwestern Ohio, Baldemar Velasquez has been fighting for the 
rights of migrant workers for more than 30 years. 
</P>
<P>
	He led a seven-year boycott of Campbell Soup Co. that  
transformed workers from sharecroppers to employees, giving them 
unemployment benefits, workers' compensation and Social Security. 
</P>
<P>
	Now Velasquez fears that not only his union but the whole fruit  
and vegetable industry in Ohio and Michigan are threatened because 
food producers can find less costly non-union labor in the South. 
</P>
<P>
	``They'll abandon this area,'' he said. ``It's about the  
survival of the industry and the growers here. We'd like to retain 
the industry.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Velasquez and the Farm Labor Organizing Committee he leads have  
enlisted labor unions, churches and minority organizations in a 
boycott of the Mount Olive Pickle Co. -- the South's largest pickle 
producer. 
</P>
<P>
	The company says it's an unfair tactic because farmers are the  
ones hiring the farm workers. 
</P>
<P>
	The farm workers union wants Mount Olive to sign contracts with  
its cucumber pickers, most of whom are temporary workers from 
Mexico and Central America. The union says the workers are forced 
to live in unsafe homes, exposed to dangerous pesticides and get 
cheated on pay and benefits. 
</P>
<P>
	If the boycott isn't successful, the union believes that  
companies such as Campbell, Heinz and Vlasic also will look to the 
South, which is considered non-union territory. 
</P>
<P>
	Each spring, hundreds of migrant workers come to the cucumber  
patches that are mixed in with the rows of corn and soybeans in 
northwestern Ohio and southeastern Michigan. 
</P>
<P>
	The two states are among the top five in cucumber production.  
Ohio's crop brings in $12.2 million a year. 
</P>
<P>
	The union has contracts with 50 growers in Ohio and 11 in  
southeastern Michigan. It's not affiliated with the better-known 
United Farm Workers, but the two unions have a history of working 
together. 
</P>
<P>
	Success came slow for the union in its early years. During the  
boycott against Campbell Soup in the 1980s, it took years before a 
church or labor group would pledge support. 
</P>
<P>
	Now as the boycott against Mount Olive begins, the union is  
counting on its old allies for support. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not starting from scratch. We know a whole lot more  
about running a boycott and putting pressure on our allies,'' said 
union spokesman Mike Ferner. 
</P>
<P>
	Velasquez and his supporters are visiting with church groups,  
student organizations and minority groups in the South -- attempting 
to draw a parallel between the struggles of the field workers and 
those of blacks. 
</P>
<P>
	Mount Olive president Bill Bryan is speaking to those same  
organizations, taking time out to personally answer questions from 
consumers. ``We think we've been wrongly targeted, because we have 
a well-known brand name and a good product,'' Bryan said from 
company headquarters in Mount Olive, N.C. 
</P>
<P>
	Mount Olive sells an estimated 80 million jars of pickles a  
year, primarily in the South and Mid-Atlantic states. 
</P>
<P>
	So far, it has been a struggle for the union to organize workers  
in North Carolina where they are paid by how much they pick. Most 
earn an average of $3.90 an hour, according to the union. 
</P>
<P>
	Farmers are reluctant to allow union representatives onto their  
land to hand out pamphlets and make their pitch. They fear higher 
wages will put them out of business. 
</P>
<P>
	``We believe we're taking very good care of our workers,'' said  
Stan Eury, executive director of the North Carolina Growers 
Association. ``We're very concerned about (the union's) willingness 
to tell misinformation about their cause.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Velasquez won't guess how long he expects the boycott to last.  
But he does offer this: 
</P>
<P>
	``We'll always have more time than the company has money.''  

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990411.0097 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-11 16:12:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Photos Show Possible Mass Grave  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Western officials today expressed  
alarm over reports of atrocities in Kosovo, saying a possible mass 
grave site had been spotted. In Belgium, NATO spokesman Jamie Shea 
showed aerial photographs of the site in Pusto Selo, southwest of 
the Kosovo capital, Pristina. British officials also said about 
100,000 ethnic Albanian men are apparently missing. Meanwhile, NATO 
continued to hammer Serb targets. Belgrade itself was unscathed in 
overnight air attacks, but attacks in and around Pristina were 
heavy. 

</P>
<P>
	US Officials Take Aim at Milosevic  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Several U.S. officials said today that  
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic should be tried for war 
crimes. ``I think he is a war criminal,'' Sen. Joseph Biden, 
D-Del., told NBC. Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott, on CBS, 
said Milosevic would be held responsible for his acts by the 
International War Crimes Tribunal. Meanwhile, some lawmakers want 
the Clinton administration to consider ground troops in the 
campaign against Milosevic. Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., urged a 
resolution that expresses support for all military options, 
including ground troops. It's ``foolishness to say that you are not 
allowed to exercise any option or at least threaten,'' he said. 

</P>
<P>
	Air Force Seeks Rescue Satellite  
</P>
<P>
	CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) -- The Air Force scrambled today to  
rescue a $250 million missile-warning satellite that was left 
stranded in a useless orbit. The Defense Support Program satellite 
was launched Friday aboard an Air Force Titan rocket. Air Force 
officials said the Boeing-built motor separated as planned from the 
satellite seven hours after liftoff. If the satellite cannot be 
salvaged, the failed mission will have cost taxpayers $682 million. 

</P>
<P>
	Iraq: Allies Hit Civilian Targets  
</P>
<P>
	BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) -- Allied planes struck civil and military  
targets in southern Iraq today, killing two people and wounding 
nine others, the Iraqi military reported. The U.S. Central Command 
confirmed that American planes had attacked Iraqi missile batteries 
100 miles south of Baghdad, but gave no word of casualties. The 
attacks were in retaliation for anti-aircraft fire and a 
surface-to-air missile attack on ``coalition aircraft,'' the 
Central Command said in a statement from its headquarters in 
Florida. 

</P>
<P>
	Ex-CIA Chief Reportedly Probed  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The nation's former top spy reportedly was the  
target of a Justice Department investigation into whether he 
mishandled sensitive information. CIA technicians found 31 secret 
files in the unsecured personal computer at the home of the former 
Director John Deutch shortly after he left the post, Newsweek 
magazine said today. The Central Intelligence Agency turned the 
case over to the department, which investigated for a year before 
deciding not to file charges, the magazine said. Deutch resigned 
from the agency in 1996. 

</P>
<P>
	Four Hurt at Black College Reunion  
</P>
<P>
	DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. (AP) -- Two shootings and two stabbings left  
four people in the hospital today during a spring break-style 
gathering known as Black College Reunion. Despite the violence, 
Mayor Bud Asher said the incidents were isolated and called the 
three-day event a success. Police are investigating whether the two 
shootings were connected because both were reported on the same 
block. 

</P>
<P>
	Gas Prices Up 14 Cents Nationwide  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- OPEC cuts in crude oil production, seasonal  
demand and fires at California refineries have pushed up the price 
of gasoline 14 cents per gallon around the country. Motorists were 
hardest hit in California, where the unweighted average price for 
regular unleaded was $1.6390. The price tag for a motorist to fill 
his car's tank at a San Francisco Chevron station today was $18.68 
for 10 1/2 gallons. 

</P>
<P>
	Three-Way Tie at Masters  
</P>
<P>
	AUGUSTA, Ga. (AP) -- Jose Maria Olazabal, Greg Norman and Steve  
Pate tied for the 63-hole lead after their front nines today at the 
Masters, where winds gusting to 35 mph made the final round a big 
guessing game. Davis Love III was 5-under after the front but found 
double-bogey disaster on No. 12. David Duval, seeking his third 
consecutive victory and ranked No. 1 in the world, rode an eagle 3 
on the par-5 No. 8 to a 3-under-par 33 on the front nine to jump 
back into the tournament. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by LISI de BOURBON  
</P>
