<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Florida Eases Plastic Surgery Rules </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) -- Florida's Board of Medicine on  
Sunday eased new policies aimed at safeguarding outpatient cosmetic 
surgery after complaints from plastic surgeons that the rules were 
too strict. 
</P>
<P>
	The state regulatory board relaxed rules approved in January  
that limited the length of office surgery and required medical 
doctors in anesthesiology to be present during operations. 
</P>
<P>
	``We do not want to micromanage surgeons,'' said Dr. Fuad  
Ashkar, a board member who proposed the compromise. ``However, we 
need to guarantee patient safety.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In January, the board voted to limit office surgery to four  
hours per operation, heeding experts who believe lengthy, 
multipurpose procedures increases risk. It also approved tougher 
anesthesiology rules; previously, nurses had been allowed to sedate 
patients without a doctor's supervision. 
</P>
<P>
	The regulations came after reports of 18 deaths in the state  
related to cosmetic surgery from 1997 to March of this year. 
</P>
<P>
	The relaxed rules expand the allowed length of procedures to six  
hours and again sanctions nurses to administer anesthesia to 
patients -- this time to patients who sign waivers. 
</P>
<P>
	The board left intact regulations abolishing overnight stays at  
doctors' facilities and reducing the amount of fat that can be 
removed from a patient during liposuction. 
</P>
<P>
	The new rulings followed public testimony from surgeons, nurses  
and representatives of statewide medical associations. 
</P>
<P>
	Other states have also adjusted policies governing use of  
sedatives in outpatient surgery after reports of problems. A law 
that goes into effect next January in California requires proof of 
training for dentists using oral sedatives. 
</P>
<P>
	The state of New Jersey tightened policies governing anesthesia  
use in doctor's offices following the death there of a young child 
who was sedated and left unmonitored. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
