<HEADLINE> Mariners' Pitcher Charged With DUI </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Seattle Mariners pitcher Mac Suzuki was charged  
with driving under the influence and hit-and-run driving following 
an accident near the Kingdome. 
</P>
<P>
	Suzuki's yellow Humvee was impounded early Friday morning after  
he was stopped by police investigating a report that an unoccupied 
car had been hit shortly after midnight PDT. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors said his blood alcohol level was close to .14  
percent, which would be well over the legal threshold of .08 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The 23-year-old rookie pleaded innocent Saturday in King County  
District Court and was freed on $1,500 bail. 
</P>
<P>
	Police Sgt. Jack Magan said he did not know the extent of the  
damage to either vehicle. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a typical DUI stop except for that the driver was a  
Mariner,'' Magan said. ``There was no effort to resist arrest. The 
driver cooperated.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Suzuki, a native of Kobe, Japan, has played seven seasons in the  
minor leagues and also appeared in six Mariners games last year and 
two this season. 
</P>
<P>
	His longest outing was Saturday night, following his release,  
when he gave up one run and two hits in three innings as the 
Mariners lost to Oakland 11-4. 
</P>
<P>
	Mariners pitching coach Stan Williams said he learned of the  
arrest only on Saturday night. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's surprising to me because I didn't even know he imbibed.  
You can't find a finer young man,'' Williams said. ``It shows you 
that ballplayers are human beings.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
