<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7:35 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Photos Show Possible Mass Grave  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Western officials today expressed  
alarm over reports of atrocities in Kosovo, saying a possible mass 
grave site had been spotted. In Belgium, NATO spokesman Jamie Shea 
showed aerial photographs of the site in Pusto Selo, southwest of 
the Kosovo capital, Pristina. British officials also said about 
100,000 ethnic Albanian men are apparently missing. Meanwhile, NATO 
continued to hammer Serb targets. Belgrade itself was unscathed in 
overnight air attacks, but attacks in and around Pristina were 
heavy. 

</P>
<P>
	US Officials Take Aim at Milosevic  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Several U.S. officials said today that  
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic should be tried for war 
crimes. ``I think he is a war criminal,'' Sen. Joseph Biden, 
D-Del., told NBC. Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott, on CBS, 
said Milosevic would be held responsible for his acts by the 
International War Crimes Tribunal. Meanwhile, some lawmakers want 
the Clinton administration to consider ground troops in the 
campaign against Milosevic. Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., urged a 
resolution that expresses support for all military options, 
including ground troops. It's ``foolishness to say that you are not 
allowed to exercise any option or at least threaten,'' he said. 

</P>
<P>
	Air Force Seeks Rescue Satellite  
</P>
<P>
	CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) -- The Air Force scrambled today to  
rescue a $250 million missile-warning satellite that was left 
stranded in a useless orbit. The Defense Support Program satellite 
was launched Friday aboard an Air Force Titan rocket. Air Force 
officials said the Boeing-built motor separated as planned from the 
satellite seven hours after liftoff. If the satellite cannot be 
salvaged, the failed mission will have cost taxpayers $682 million. 

</P>
<P>
	Iraq: Allies Hit Civilian Targets  
</P>
<P>
	BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) -- Allied planes struck civil and military  
targets in southern Iraq today, killing two people and wounding 
nine others, the Iraqi military reported. The U.S. Central Command 
confirmed that American planes had attacked Iraqi missile batteries 
100 miles south of Baghdad, but gave no word of casualties. The 
attacks were in retaliation for anti-aircraft fire and a 
surface-to-air missile attack on ``coalition aircraft,'' the 
Central Command said in a statement from its headquarters in 
Florida. 

</P>
<P>
	Ex-CIA Chief Reportedly Probed  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The nation's former top spy reportedly was the  
target of a Justice Department investigation into whether he 
mishandled sensitive information. CIA technicians found 31 secret 
files in the unsecured personal computer at the home of the former 
Director John Deutch shortly after he left the post, Newsweek 
magazine said today. The Central Intelligence Agency turned the 
case over to the department, which investigated for a year before 
deciding not to file charges, the magazine said. Deutch resigned 
from the agency in 1996. 

</P>
<P>
	Four Hurt at Black College Reunion  
</P>
<P>
	DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. (AP) -- Two shootings and two stabbings left  
four people in the hospital today during a spring break-style 
gathering known as Black College Reunion. Despite the violence, 
Mayor Bud Asher said the incidents were isolated and called the 
three-day event a success. Police are investigating whether the two 
shootings were connected because both were reported on the same 
block. 

</P>
<P>
	Gas Prices Up 14 Cents Nationwide  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- OPEC cuts in crude oil production, seasonal  
demand and fires at California refineries have pushed up the price 
of gasoline 14 cents per gallon around the country. Motorists were 
hardest hit in California, where the unweighted average price for 
regular unleaded was $1.6390. The price tag for a motorist to fill 
his car's tank at a San Francisco Chevron station today was $18.68 
for 10 1/2 gallons. 

</P>
<P>
	Olazabal Wins Masters  
</P>
<P>
	AUGUSTA, Ga. (AP) -- Jose Maria Olazabal, a 33-year-old Spaniard,  
won the Masters for the second time today. Olazabal survived the 
conditions at Augusta National by not making a bogey over the final 
13 holes. He finished his 1-under 71 with a 4-foot par putt. 
Olazabal shot a 280 for the tournament to beat Davis Love III by 
two strokes. It was the highest winning score in the Masters in 10 
years. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by LISI de BOURBON  
