<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Female Inmates Report Child Abuse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Inmates of state prisons and local jails,  
especially woman, are much more likely than the general population 
to have suffered physical or sexual abuse as children, the Justice 
Department reports. 
</P>
<P>
	The reports of abuse are overwhelmingly concentrated among  
female inmates, who represent only a little over 7 percent of the 
state prison and jail population. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 36 percent of the female state prison and jail inmates  
surveyed in 1996 and 1997 reported they were abused sexually or 
physically at age 17 or younger, the department's Bureau of Justice 
Statistics said Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	By comparison, 16 studies of child abuse in the general  
population found that 12 percent to 17 percent of women were abused 
as children, the bureau said. 
</P>
<P>
	Among male inmates of state prisons, 14 percent said they  
suffered child abuse, compared with 5 percent to 8 percent of the 
general male population, the study found. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not surprised,'' said Eleanor Smeal, president of the  
Feminist Majority Foundation. ``The women who end up behind bars 
have had a very hard life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Childhood abuse increases the risk that anyone -- female or  
male -- could end up in prison,'' Smeal said. ``Women abused as 
children have their whole self-image changed. They believe they are 
bad. They end up in relationships with men who abuse them and in 
risky situations.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Some end up in drug abuse and are forced into prostitution,''  
she added. ``The police arrest prostitutes, but usually not their 
male clients. '' 
</P>
<P>
	The survey found alcohol and drug abuse was higher among inmates  
who suffered abuse than among those who did not. Among state prison 
inmates, 80 percent of the abused women and 76 percent of the 
abused men had used illegal drugs regularly, compared with 65 
percent of the women and 68 percent of the men who had not been 
abused. 
</P>
<P>
	Counting sexual or physical abuse at any age before  
imprisonment, the survey found that nearly half of the women in 
prison or jail or on probation had suffered such attacks, compared 
with only 10 percent of the men in the same circumstances. 
</P>
<P>
	This five-to-one ratio may simply reflect the established fact  
that more women than men suffer physical or sexual abuse. In 
addition to differences in size and strength, ``men are trained to 
fight back, and women are trained to cry,'' Smeal said. ``So women 
are a much more abused population than men.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The survey also found that one-third of women in state prisons  
and one-quarter of those in local jails had been raped before they 
were incarcerated. Only 3 percent of men reported they had been 
raped before incarceration. 
</P>
<P>
	Abused state prisoners were more likely than those not abused to  
have ever served time for a violent crime. Among males, 76 percent 
of abused inmates, compared with 61 percent of those not abused, 
had a current or past sentence for a violent offense. Among women, 
45 percent of the abused, but only 29 percent of those not abused, 
had ever served a sentence for violence. 
</P>
<P>
	Prisoners reported higher levels of abuse if they grew up at  
least partly in foster care rather than with parents, if their 
parents were heavy drug or alcohol users or if a family member had 
been imprisoned. The study noted that many foster children had been 
removed from homes where they were abused by parents. 
</P>
<P>
	The study found little difference in the percentage of abused  
parents growing up with one parent or those with two parents. 
</P>
</TEXT>
