<HEADLINE> Diamondbacks Looking for Change </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- The Arizona Diamondbacks finally play their home  
opener Monday night, and they hope 10 games at Bank One Ballpark 
will bring a reversal of fortune following a 1-5 start. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'll get back home and try to change things,'' shortstop Tony  
Batista said. ``I don't know if it will be any easier. It's not 
easy anywhere.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Motivation should be no problem for the Diamondbacks, because  
Los Angeles is expected to send Chan Ho Park to the mound against 
Arizona's Andy Benes in the first game of a four-game series 
between the two NL West rivals. 
</P>
<P>
	Last Tuesday, the Diamondbacks accused Park of intentionally  
throwing at Matt Williams' head after Williams homered off him. 
</P>
<P>
	The dugouts emptied for some shoving and a lot of name-calling,  
and the umpires warned both teams not to retaliate. Los Angeles won 
the game 3-2 in 10 innings, one of two extra-inning victories in 
the Dodgers' sweep. 
</P>
<P>
	Park was not scheduled to pitch in the Diamondbacks series, but  
Los Angeles' game against San Diego Sunday was rained out, the 
first rainout at Dodger Stadium in 11 years. Park's start then was 
moved back a day to Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Benes (0-1, 9.64 ERA) was pounded by the Dodgers in Arizona's  
6-4 loss in his first game last Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The rainout also washed out Thursday's scheduled rematch between  
Randy Johnson and Kevin Brown. Johnson will go Thursday, but with 
the Dodgers rotation pushed back a day, his opponent likely will be 
Darren Dreifort. 
</P>
<P>
	The Diamondbacks were playing down any payback factor in the  
Dodgers' series. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's always nice to have the home field on our side,'' manager  
Buck Showalter said. ``We played them in LA and didn't have much to 
show for it. It's not revenge we're after. Whether it's LA, the 
Marlins or the Braves, we still have to beat them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Diamondbacks limp home with three extra-inning losses.  
Closer Gregg Olson has blown three save chances, the latest in a 
3-2 loss to Atlanta on Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Todd Stottlemyre had gotten Arizona to the ninth inning, but  
Olson gave up two runs and second baseman Jay Bell committed a 
costly error. 
</P>
<P>
	The Diamondbacks were 1-2 in Atlanta, with the only victory  
coming in Johnson's complete game, 15-strikeout 8-3 performance on 
Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	``This has been a tough stretch travelwise,'' said Stottlemyre,  
who has yet to get a decision despite two strong performances. ``We 
played LA and then had to come across the country and play Atlanta. 
There's no question about it. It will be good to get home.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The San Francisco Giants play a three-game series at Bank One  
Ballpark beginning Friday. The homestand concludes next week with 
three against the Philadelphia Phillies. 
</P>
<P>
	While relief pitching has been a major headache for the  
Diamondbacks, there have been some positive aspects. The starting 
rotation has been as strong as advertised, and the Diamondbacks 
have hit 13 home runs in six games against some of the best 
pitching in the NL. 
</P>
<P>
	Arizona might have Tony Womack, who has been on the disabled  
list with a fractured right wrist. Womack played last week for 
Triple-A Tucson. The NL leader in stolen bases the last two 
seasons, Womack is slated to be Arizona's leadoff batter. 
</P>
<P>
	His return likely will mean Bernard Gilkey will go to the bench,  
even though Gilkey has gotten off to a good start. 
</P>
<P>
	``Basically, we want to play sound baseball,'' Bell said. ``If  
we do, eventually things will come our way.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
