<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mid-Level Stocks Could Be Bargain / Ticker Talk  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- In the midst of the great Wall Street debate  
over the relative merits of big stocks vs. small, some analysts 
think a worthy answer lies in the middle. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the so-called mid-capitalization, or mid-cap, stocks  
haven't soared to the sky-high valuations that some blue chips and 
technology giants have reached lately. 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time, their partisans say mid-cap companies may have  
a better chance of competing successfully in the world economy of 
the early 21st century than smaller companies, many of whose stocks 
have been in a prolonged slump. 
</P>
<P>
	Although it may be a step down from the blue-chip realm,  
investing in mid-caps isn't exactly slumming. The mid-cap ranks 
include names like Tiffany &AMP; Co., Harley-Davidson, Abercrombie &AMP; 
Fitch and Young &AMP; Rubicam Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	In recent years, while blue chips have soared and small stocks  
have sagged, mid-cap stock performance has generally been, well, 
middling. 
</P>
<P>
	Over the 12 months through March 31, according to preliminary  
numbers from CDA Wiesenberger in Rockville, Md., stock mutual funds 
modeled on the blue-chip Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index posted a 17.92 
percent gain, while small-cap funds tumbled 15.37 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The average mid-cap fund approximately split that gaping  
33-point difference, edging up 3.73 percent. Mid-caps showed 
stirrings of life in March, however, climbing more than 5 percent 
to outpace large stocks, small stocks, the S&AMP;P 500 funds and just 
about everybody else in the ranks of diversified domestic stock 
funds. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have been singing the praises of the midcap sector of late,  
as we shy away from the relatively high valuations of large-cap 
growth stocks,'' says A. Marshall Acuff, investment strategist at 
Salomon Smith Barney Inc. ``Faster earnings growth is the reason we 
believe that select mid-caps will continue to close the gap with 
large-caps.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Definitions of what constitutes ``mid-cap'' status can very  
considerably on Wall Street. Acuff sets the boundaries at $1 
billion to $10 billion in market capitalization, or the total value 
of shares outstanding. 
</P>
<P>
	Of course, the potential for greater earnings growth has long  
been a prime reason cited by ``emerging-growth'' advocates for 
investing in small, or even micro-cap, stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	But these days, says Edward Yardeni, chief economist at Deutsche  
Bank Securities Inc., the economic picture ``is not a happy one for 
small companies. They face enormous competition. They don't have as 
much access to global markets as bigger companies. They don't have 
resources to innovate and to leverage innovations in global 
markets. 
</P>
<P>
	``Of course, this is a caricature,'' Yardeni adds. ``There are  
bound to be some gems out there. But they are likely to be 
purchased by Microsoft before they become the next Microsoft.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In Yardeni's eyes, conditions are very bullish for the small  
universe of big-cap market leaders. The problem is that everyone 
knows this and their stock prices are not cheap. 
</P>
<P>
	Argues Acuff: ``The global growth that boosted the performance  
of the large multinationals has become an anchor as global turmoil 
continues. While some regions of the world may be starting to 
improve, we believe that large-cap valuations already reflect these 
expectations. 
</P>
<P>
	``If, as we expect, a rebound in Asia and Latin America takes  
some time to work through, large-cap valuations could suffer in the 
meantime. However, the powerful domestic economy will continue to 
drive demand, in our opinion, and the beneficiaries will be those 
companies with a strong domestic presence, such as the mid-caps.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990411.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-11 14:33:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Medicines May Prevent Colon Cancer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- A combination of aspirin and  
cholesterol-lowering drugs, already used by millions of Americans 
to keep their hearts healthy, may also significantly lower their 
risk of colon cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	New research presented Sunday suggests that these two ubiquitous  
medicines appear to offer a potent -- if unintended -- shield against 
a disease that kills about 48,000 a year in the U.S. 
</P>
<P>
	Data from both people and animal studies suggest that together  
they may eliminate cells in the earliest stages of cancer before 
they grow into full-blown malignancy. 
</P>
<P>
	The work is based on a new analysis of the powerful class of  
cholesterol-lowering drugs known as statins. The research, 
conducted by doctors from St. Luke's-Roosevelt Hospital Center in 
New York City, was released at the annual scientific meeting of the 
American Association for Cancer Research. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a wonderful example of drugs that are already  
available that may have an entirely different and important use,'' 
said Dr. Frank Rauscher of the Wistar Institute in Philadelphia. 
</P>
<P>
	Protective effects of aspirin and similar inflammation-fighting  
medicines against colon cancer are already suspected from earlier 
studies. But the possible role of the statin drugs has been much 
less clear. 
</P>
<P>
	Doctors often prescribe aspirin and statins at the same time to  
prevent heart disease. Statins lower high cholesterol levels that 
clog the heart arteries, while aspirin makes the blood less likely 
to form clots that get stuck in tortuously narrowed arteries. 
</P>
<P>
	The new work suggests that the same drugs prevent colon cancer  
by entirely different mechanisms. Although the precise actions are 
still murky, scientists theorize that they stop cells in the 
earliest stages of cancer from dividing and induce them to commit 
suicide. 
</P>
<P>
	No human studies have been set up specifically to test these  
theories. However, data are available from several large studies on 
heart patients. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Banke Agarwal and colleagues examined the results of three  
of these studies involving more then 15,000 patients. The studies 
were designed to test how well Mevacor and other statins ward off 
heart attacks. 
</P>
<P>
	Agarwal said the studies suggest that the statins protect  
against colon cancer, but only when combined with aspirin. In one 
of the studies, nearly all of the volunteers took aspirin. Those 
also getting a statin had a 43 percent reduction in colon cancer. 
However, in another of the studies, only 17 percent took aspirin, 
and there was no cancer reduction among patients receiving a statin 
drug. 
</P>
<P>
	``On their own, statins may not decrease colon cancer. They only  
increase the effect of aspirin against cancer,'' said Agarwal. 
</P>
<P>
	To check this idea, the researchers tested Mevacor and an  
aspirin-like drug called sulindac on rats at risk of developing 
pre-cancerous colon growths. They found that Mevacor reduced these 
growths by 12 percent, while sulindac reduced them by 15 percent. 
But together they reduced the growths by 28 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Agarwal said that while the results are promising, more research  
is necessary before doctors prescribe these drugs solely to prevent 
colon cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	In another study at the meeting, Dr. Tao Liu presented data  
suggesting that genetic testing may help identify people at high 
risk of rare inherited forms of colon cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	These cancers often occur because of errors in so-called  
mismatch repair genes, which look for copying errors that crop up 
in genes during the production of new cells. 
</P>
<P>
	The researchers tried out an experimental test that looks for  
these bad repair genes. They found 70 percent of people with the 
inherited colon cancer tested positive with this method. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
