<HEADLINE> Mets Hobble Home for Opener </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Mike Piazza is on the disabled list with a bum  
knee. 
</P>
<P>
	Rick Reed is hobbling with a strained Achillies' tendon.  
</P>
<P>
	While the Mets are winning, they head into Monday's home opener  
against Florida a little beat up. 
</P>
<P>
	``A championship team deals with injuries all year, and the fact  
that it's Mike makes it a big injury for us to overcome,'' Orel 
Hershiser said after Sunday's 6-3 win at Montreal. ``It's the first 
hurdle we've got to clear to have a good year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bobby Jones (1-0) pitches against Livan Hernandez (0-1) on what  
figures to be a wet, cold day at Shea Stadium. The Mets had an 
advance sale of about 45,000 coming in. 
</P>
<P>
	``It just feels like the season didn't start yet because we've  
been on the road, so tomorrow I guess the season will start,'' 
closer John Franco said after Sunday's game. ``We'll have our own 
crowd behind us, rather than everyone else's. We've played two home 
openers, Florida and here, and now we'll have our own, and guys can 
get settled in and get apartments and get used to the home 
surroundings. 
</P>
<P>
	It will be the Mets' first game at Shea Stadium since their  
season-ending flop last year, when they went 0-5 and scored just 
seven runs, finishing one game behind Chicago and San Francisco in 
the NL wild-card race. 
</P>
<P>
	It also will be Bobby Bonilla's first game at Shea Stadium in a  
Mets uniform since 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've had some pretty good opening days for New York, so that's  
one positive thing,'' Bonilla said. ``But everybody's really pretty 
fired up. We were able to do a nice job here in Montreal, which was 
very important.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Mets are 5-2 and have won five of six since losing their  
opener at Miami last Monday. But Piazza's absence will be sorely 
felt. 
</P>
<P>
	New York's decision to sign the six-time All-Star to a $91  
million, seven-year contract signaled a renewed commitment by 
ownership to field a contender. 
</P>
<P>
	Al Leiter then decided to stay, too, getting a $32 million,  
four-year contract, and free agent third baseman Robin Ventura 
signed a $32 million, four-year contract. The Mets also acquired 
Bonilla and reliever Armando Benitez in trades, and signed Rickey 
Henderson and Hershiser. 
</P>
<P>
	Piazza was placed on the 15-day disabled list Sunday, even  
though he didn't feel the injury was that severe. Without Piazza, 
Todd Pratt becomes the starting catcher for at least 2-3 weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm sure they'll be disappointed that he's not there because  
he's such a great player,'' said first baseman John Olerud said. 
``He's the guy for us, offensively-speaking, and so it definitely 
hurts having him out of the lineup. 
</P>
<P>
	``But I think we have a good team. We have a lot of good guys on  
this team, guys that can swing the bat, so hopefully we can pick up 
the slack until he comes back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Reed was due to have an MRI on Monday. He was hurt Sunday trying  
to stretch his game-tying RBI single into a double. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't want to miss my next start,'' he said. ``I don't think  
I will. It started to stiffen up but after I got some ice I was 
able to walk around.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
