<HEADLINE> Israel May Take Control of Nazareth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- Nazareth's mayor said Sunday he will reject any  
move by Israel to take control of the locally elected city council, 
paralyzed by simmering Christian-Muslim tensions in the town of 
Jesus' boyhood. 
</P>
<P>
	Mayor Ramez Jeraisi said he fears Israel might dissolve the body  
and appoint its own representatives to the council, where parties 
elected in November have so far failed to cobble together a 
coalition. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the principal obstacles to a coalition is a sectarian  
dispute over a plan to build a plaza to accommodate the anticipated 
flood of Christian pilgrims for the millennium. Muslims want the 
site for a mosque. 
</P>
<P>
	Israeli Interior Minister Eli Suissa launched an inquiry Sunday  
into the political impasse. With the year 2000 only eight months 
away, Christian-Muslim tensions are harming Israel's plans to turn 
Nazareth into a showcase now that Bethlehem, Jesus' traditional 
birthplace, is under full Palestinian control. 
</P>
<P>
	``We cannot allow the city of Nazareth, where millions of  
pilgrims are anticipated in 2000, not to function as it should,'' 
Suissa said in a statement released by his office. 
</P>
<P>
	The dispute over the half-acre plot next to the Church of the  
Annunciation erupted into violence last week during Easter 
celebrations. 
</P>
<P>
	Townspeople, who once prided themselves on their coexistence,  
saw cars overturned, stores firebombed and a dozen people injured 
in stoning attacks. 
</P>
<P>
	Jeraisi, who is a Christian, told The Associated Press that he  
has received several death threats, the most recent a few days ago. 
He said he would resign if Israel makes its own appointments to the 
council. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will struggle against it, and we will not accept such a  
step,'' he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
