<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Salon Industry Needs Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- For beauty salons across the country, the strong  
economy is both a blessing and a curse. 
</P>
<P>
	Business is brisk. But the low unemployment rate means workers  
are hard to come by. 
</P>
<P>
	``Now it's at a crisis situation,'' said Henri Blaine, owner of  
beauty schools in Connecticut and Massachusetts that send recent 
graduates to salons. ``Salon owners give me hell. What can I do? 
It's a tight labor market.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Blaine said about 500 job postings remain unfilled at his six  
Blaine Beauty Career Schools. 
</P>
<P>
	Dellaria Salons, which has 25 locations throughout New England,  
turns away thousands of clients each week because it doesn't have 
enough hairdressers to handle the load, according to Nino Micozzi, 
president and chief executive officer of the company. 
</P>
<P>
	That translates into a loss of more than $80,000 a week, Micozzi  
groused as he punched in the figures on a calculator. 
</P>
<P>
	``We could hire 50 to 75 tomorrow morning and guarantee $25,000  
a year to start,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Micozzi's plight highlights the challenge of hair salons that  
are finding themselves without enough stylists to curl, color and 
snip in an industry that touts flexible hours, benefits and decent 
wages. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're competing not necessarily against other hair firms but  
other jobs in general,'' said Paul Finkelstein, chief executive 
officer of Regis Corp., the Minneapolis-based giant that owns more 
than 4,000 salons nationwide, including the SuperCuts and Trade 
Secrets chains. 
</P>
<P>
	Part of the problem, some say, is a lack of prestige accorded to  
the hairdressing industry. Many creative and talented people don't 
think of hairdressing as a viable career, despite the success of 
famed stylists like New York's Frederic Fekkai and Boston's Mario 
Russo, who have parlayed their expertise into haircuts that can 
cost upward of $400. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some people make millions,'' said Jackie Summers, editorial  
director of Modern Salon Magazine, a Chicago-based trade 
publication. ``A lot of people think of hairdressers as low-wage 
people and it's not really always the case.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The lucrative salon industry, including products and services,  
is a $45 billion market in the United States, according to Modern 
Salon. And it continues to grow as clients clamor for more services 
-- especially coloring, which has grown in popularity in recent 
years. 
</P>
<P>
	``Young people do it for the cosmetic value and older baby  
boomers do it for that and to start covering up the gray,'' Summers 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	For salons desperate for stylists, some have started offering  
perks like free training and 401K plans. Many businesses also have 
begun targeting students at high schools, hosting job fairs, 
offering tuition grants and advertising on television, Summer said. 
</P>
<P>
	Some professionals said the little-known rewards of the  
hairstyling industry include one intangible: helping others. 
</P>
<P>
	At Salon Mario Russo on Newbury Street in Boston, amid the hum  
of blow dryers, Corey Henderson, 30, said stylists benefit from -- 
as well as perform services for -- their customers. 
</P>
<P>
	``This brings in a sense of creativity and warmth,'' Henderson  
gushed. ``I love my clients and learn something from them.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
