<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Orioles Activate DeShields </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- The Baltimore Orioles activated second baseman  
Delino DeShields from the disabled list and added pitcher Doug 
Linton to the 25-man roster Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Both players were in the starting lineup against the Toronto  
Blue Jays. DeShields, returning from a broken left thumb, batted 
eighth and Linton made his first appearance in the majors since 
1996. 
</P>
<P>
	To make room on the roster, the Orioles optioned infielder Jesse  
Garcia and left-handed pitcher Doug Johns to Triple-A Rochester of 
the International League. 
</P>
<P>
	DeShields signed a three-year contract as a free agent in  
December but was forced to wait to make his debut with the Orioles 
after fracturing his thumb March 4 in an intrasquad game. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm just ready to play ball. That's it,'' DeShields said. ``I  
knew I'd be back. It's just a matter of being patient.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Linton's last previous major league start and appearance came on  
Sept. 11, 1996 with the Kansas City Royals. The right-hander 
underwent surgery on his right elbow in March 1997 and missed the 
entire season. 
</P>
<P>
	He spent the 1998 season with Triple-A Salt Lake, an affiliate  
of the Minnesota Twins, and signed as a free agent with Baltimore 
in December. 
</P>
<P>
	Linton, 34, had a 0.90 ERA in seven appearances during spring  
training. 
</P>
<P>
	Garcia made two fine plays at second base for the Orioles in  
their 3-2 exhibition win over Cuba on March 28 and got a single in 
his first at-bat in the majors Saturday. He accepted the demotion 
with no remorse. 
</P>
<P>
	``I felt comfortable. They put me in and I did what they asked  
me to do,'' he said. ``It's been sweet for me. I have nothing to 
complain about.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Garcia said he will box the ball representing his first  
major-league hit, a single, and mail it to his mother. 
</P>
<P>
	He will alternate between shortstop and second base at  
Rochester. Jerry Hairston Jr., another infield prospect at 
Rochester, also plays second and shortstop. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm just going to go down there, do the same things I did here  
and get back as soon as I can,'' Garcia said. 
</P>
<P>
	Johns made two appearances this season with Baltimore, both in  
long relief. He was arrested on Monday, hours after the Orioles 
opened the season with a win over Tampa Bay, and charged with 
drunken driven and possession of marijuana. 
</P>
<P>
	Manager Ray Miller said the arrest had no bearing on the  
decision to send him to the minor leagues. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
